<FIRST>u i AM-Angola-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0810 02-12 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0810,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angola Claims South African Troops Violated Peace Accord</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to note that report monitored in Lisbon;
picks up 3rd graf `The Pretoria...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola said its troops killed 40 South
African soldiers who crossed the border, violating a regional peace
agreement, the Angolan news agency ANGOP reported Sunday.
   The Marxist government protested to South Africa about the
incident that also left seven Angolan soldiers dead, said the report
monitored in Lisbon.
   The Pretoria government rejected the charge and requested an
immediate meeting of a commission monitoring the peace accord to
discuss the matter.
   The Angolan Defense Ministry statement issued Saturday said South
African troops on Wednesday crossed into Angola from neighboring
Namibia in support of Angolan rebels, ANGOP reported.
   The Angolan government troops drove the South Africans back to
the Namibian frontier after heavy fighting that ended early Friday,
ANGOP reported. It said 40 South African soldiers were
   In Pretoria, the South African Foreign Affairs Department said it
replied ``in the strongest terms'' to the allegations contained in a
protest note sent by Angola's government.
   In the statement Sunday, South Africa said it was on standby to
attend an urgent meeting of the monitoring commission in Luanda, the
Angolan capital, to discuss Angola's allegations.
   The U.S. State Department said last week it had no evidence that
any South African troops entered Angola.
   South African military authorities say their forces are strictly
observing the U.S.-brokered peace agreement signed in December. The
agreement bars South African military aid to the anti-Marxist rebels
in Angola and calls for independence of Namibia from South African
control.
   The peace accord established a joint commission, comprised of
South African, Cuban and Angolan representatives, to monitor
observance of the various provisions.
   As part of the peace agreement, about 50,000 Cuban troops were to
withdraw from Angola, where they have been helping the government
fight the rebels belonging to the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola.
   The rebel group rejects the peace accords and has vowed to
continue fighting until the Angolan government agrees to share power.
   The area where the fighting reportedly took place is near a
stretch of the border between Angola and Namibia which does not have
monitoring posts called for in the peace agreement.
   The rebels said Saturday that 275 government soldiers died in
heavy fighting last week when 4,000 guerrillas clashed with the
Angolan army in southern Cuando Cubango province.
   The rebels denied South African troops participated in the
fighting.
</TEXT>
