<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bundy Meeting,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators To Discuss Bundy Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmiting to restore overline.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers from states where Ted Bundy killed
or may have killed will meet next week at the FBI's Behavioral
Science Laboratory in Quantico, Va.
   Bundy died in the electric chair in Starke, Fla., on Jan. 24 for
the 1978 murder of 12-year-old Kimberly Leach of Lake City, Fla.
   One of the key figures expected at the week-long gathering is
Bill Hagmeier, an FBI agent who interviewed Bundy extensively and
sat in on many of the interviews Bundy gave in the week before he
died.
   The number of known Bundy victims is between 23 and 30, based on
the confessions he gave in the days before his death. Some law
enforcment officials believed he committed many more murders than
those he confessed to.
   States in which Bundy confessed to killings include Washington,
Utah, Colorado and Florida, but other states with unsolved killings
have also expressed interest in the former law school student.
</TEXT>
