<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     02-12 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Adviser Warns Followers Against Wildcat Strikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An adviser to Solidarity leader Lech Walesa
warned Sunday that the banned union would be blamed for wildcat
strikes and called on supporters to show discipline and reject such
actions.
   At a church frequented by Walesa, the Rev. Henryk Jankowski, an
adviser to the Solidarity chief, suggested the strikes were
provocations at a time when the union is trying to win status during
its crucial talks with the government. The talks began Feb. 6.
   A strike at a steel mill in southern Poland has not received
support from Solidarity or the government-sanctioned OPZZ trade
union alliance.
   ``No one will claim responsibility for the currently organized
strikes, not the OPZZ, not the left and not the right,'' Jankowski
said. ``So again, Solidarity will be blamed.
   ``I understand that at this moment the life of the Polish family
is very difficult. Today all the more so we are obliged to show a
certain discipline,'' he said.
   Walesa did not attend the Mass at St. Brygida's Church where
Jankowski spoke and he did not authorize the statement, Walesa and
church officials said later.
   After the Mass, attended by 4,000 people, about 500 people staged
a protest march to the train station.
   Demonstrators chanted ``Solidarity'' and ``Down with Communism''
and some threw stones at riot police shepherding the march toward
the station. Police blocked the marchers and at one point charged
them but did not use their riot truncheons.
   A strike at the Laziska steel mill in southern Poland that began
Friday over wages also continued, the state-run news agency PAP
said. A Solidarity spokeswoman said workers at the mill said their
action was spontaneous and not led by any union.
   The state PAP news service Sunday reported the end of a three-day
strike led by the OPZZ at two departments of the Marceli Nowotko
steel plant in Ostrowiec Swietkrzyzskia in central Poland.
   Workers who had opposed the distribution of the plant's pay
agreed to continue with the present pay system until May 15, when
wages will be reevaluated, PAP said.
   A strike over pay by transport workers in Piotrkow Trybunalski, a
central Polish provincial city of 80,000 people, continued. The
strike began Friday and is backed by the official trade union OPZZ.
</TEXT>
