<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Bolte     02-12 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Bolte,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Army Vice Chief of Staff Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Lawrence Bolte, a four-star
general who was the Army's vice chief of staff during the mid-1950s,
died Saturday. He was 93.
   Bolte, who retired from active duty in 1955, was a company
commander in World War I. As a major general in World War II, he
commanded the 34th Infantry Division in Italy.
   After the war he served as Army Ground Forces chief of staff and
chairman of the Inter-American Defense Board. He was the Army
commander in chief in Europe in 1952 and 1953.
   He served as Army vice chief of staff, the number-two position in
the service, from October 1953 until his retirement in April 1955.
   His decorations included two Distinguished Service Medals, the
Silver Star, the Legion of Merit and the Purple Heart.
</TEXT>
