<HEAD>Nuclear-Powered Submarine Commissioned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that submarine will not be the first
to carry cruise missiles. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Thirty-five protesters
...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nuclear-powered attack submarine USS
Pasadena joined the Navy's fleet Saturday during commissioning
ceremonies that spurred a peaceful demonstration by anti-nuclear
weapons protesters.
   Adm. Carlisle A.H. Trost, chief of naval operations, praised the
Pasadena as the ``most capable attack submarine in the world.'' The
submarine was built at the Electric Boat shipyard here.
   Thirty-five protesters from various New England-based
anti-nuclear weapons groups demonstrated outside the submarine base
in Groton. Joanne Sheehan, of the Norwich-based War Resisters
League, described the protest as a ``simple vigil.''
   ``It was important for people going to the ceremonies to show
them there is opposition to these weapons,'' she said.
   Pasadena is the first submarine and the third Navy ship to bear
the California city's name. The 360-foot submarine displaces 6,900
tons and will carry a crew of 12 officers and 115 enlisted men.
