<FIRST>u a AM-FireDeaths     02-12 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire Deaths,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Die In House Fire; Crack In Chimney Blamed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire swept through a farm house from a
faulty chimney early Saturday, killing eight family members while
they slept, officials said.
   Two family members escaped the 3 a.m. fire in a rural community
seven miles from this eastern Arkansas town, 75 miles northeast of
Little Rock.
   ``The fire marshal thinks the chimney had a crack in it,'' said
Woodruff County Sheriff Leon Creasey said Saturday night. ``This
fire just raced through the house.''
   Creasey identified the dead as Bernice Gibbs, 46, and six of her
children, ages 15 to 30, and a 2-year-old granddaughter. Mrs. Gibbs'
husband, J.B. Gibbs and their daughter, Angela, escaped. Their ages
were unavailable.
   Creasey said a wood stove was attached to the chimney.
   The sheriff said victim's bodies were found in their beds.
   ``They never knew what hit them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
