<FILEID>AP-NR-02-12-89 0048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-911Disruption     02-12 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-911 Disruption,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emergency 911 System Breaks Down; Hundreds Of Calls Unanswered</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Forrest and Lissa are cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of calls to the police and fire
departments' 911 emergency number went unanswered Saturday because
of a technical problem that knocked out the system for more than
four hours.
   Authorities said they plan to investigate whether the outage, the
first in the 911 system's five years of operation, resulted in
injury, death or fire damage that could have been avoided had the
system been working properly.
   ``At this point we just don't know,'' said police Capt. Forrest
Lewallen. ``I can say that this is a very serious problem. It is
something that quite obviously we'll have to find remedies to ensure
that it never happens again.''
   The problems began at 1 p.m. when equipment that allows the
Police Department to transfer calls to the Fire Department stopped
working, said Lissa Zanville, a spokeswoman for Pacific Bell, which
operates the system.
   The equipment failure created a backlog that allowed only one in
five calls to reach a 911 operator at the central communications
center in Los Angeles, where all 911 calls within city limits are
directed, she said.
   From 3 to 3:40 p.m., the system went down entirely and no calls
got through. By 5:14 p.m., Pacific Bell technicians had the system
working again, Ms. Zanville said.
   The number of calls that went unanswered was unknown, but the
system normally handles 5,000 to 7,000 calls a day, and a four-hour
breakdown would easily have left hundreds of calls unanswered, said
Lewallen.
   Not all of those unanswered calls would be emergencies. Lewallen
said that about 75 percent of the 4 million calls dialed each year
on 911 are emergencies, with the rest usually non-emergency calls or
pranks.
   The Sheriff's Department and the county Fire Department, which
don't operate on the city's communications system, were unaffected
by the outage, authorities said.
</TEXT>
