<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan-Iran 1stLd-Writethru   02-12 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0650,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Releases 20 Iranian Prisoners</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, ``Foreign Ministry..., to CORRECT spelling of
spokesman, Amani sted Manai. Pick up 4th pvs, ``They're being...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan on Saturday released 20
Iranians imprisoned for political crimes, extending an olive branch
to the Tehran government.
   Iran rebuffed the move and most of the freed prisoners claimed
they had been beaten and tortured by the Afghans.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said the prisoners
were released to commemorate the 10th anniversary of the revolution
in Iran that brought Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini to power.
   ``They be being released as goodwill gesture toward the Iranian
government,'' Amani told a news conference.
   Iran's highest-raking diplomat in Kabul, Charge d'Affairs Hussein
Intizari, welcomed the release but said it would not help improve
relations between Kabul and Tehran.
   Iran supports the efforts of the Moslem guerrillas, or
mujahedeen, fighting to overthrow the government of President Najib,
who has been supported by Soviet troops since December 1979. Soviet
forces are in the final days of a withdrawal to be completed by
Wednesday under a U.N.-sponsored agreement.
   ``We have not recognized this government for the past 10 years.
How can it improve relations?'' Intizari asked shortly before he
greeted the former prisoners at a hotel in Kabul.
   ``We are waiting for a government with the mujahedeen,'' he said.
   The 20 men had been imprisoned for 2 to 10 years after they were
tried and convicted of various political crimes, including aiding
the Moslem rebels.
   All appeared to be in good health, although many showed reporters
scars they said were caused by cigarette brns, missing teeth, and
said they had were repeatedly beaten and tortured.
   The Afghan government had no immediate comment on the allegations.
   Seventeen of the men were to be flown to Tehran on Sunday,
Intizari said. One man claimd he was Afghan and will stay in the
country. The other two said they did not want to go back to Iran and
were released to the International Red Cross in Kabul.
