<HEAD>Report: U.S. Wants Cuba To Help Fight Drug War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is looking to Cuba as an ally
in the war against illegal drugs, according to a published report.
   The New York Daily News in its Sunday editions quoted
unidentified sources as saying that, despite the longtime freeze in
relations between the United States and Cuba, ``initiatives are
being discussed'' through numerous channels with Cuban President
Fidel Castro, seeking his cooperation in stopping drug shipments
from South America.
   The newspaper quoted unidentified U.S. government officials as
saying that the contacts are motivated by the United States'
inability to stem the flow of illegal drugs.
   The ``cautious'' contacts with the Communist country grew out of
a December meeting in Havana between Castro and a visiting American
delegation that included U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., chairman
of the House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control, the
News reported.
   In the past, the United States has accused Castro of harboring
drug traffickers and encouraging them to smuggle illegal drugs to
the United States.
   After his visit with Castro, Rangel told U.S. officials that
``Cuba wants very much to work with both the United States and Latin
America on narcotics control,'' the Daily News reported
   Should the United States and Cuba agree to cooperate in the war
on drugs, the U.S. government could face an uproar from the
Cuban-American community, the News said.
