<FIRST>u i BC-SriLanka-Massacre 1stLd-Writethru   02-12 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sri Lanka-Massacre, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0665,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamil Rebels Kill 34 In Sleeping Village</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with more killings. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil rebels armed with automatic
rifles, machetes and clubs attacked a remote jungle village in
central Sri Lanka and killed 34 Sinhalese, authorities said Sunday.
   Elsewhere in the island nation, nine other people were killed as
violence escalated with the approach of Wednesday's parliamentary
election. One of the victims was an opposition party candidate, the
14th would-be legislator to die since campaigning started five weeks
ago.
   More than 50 rebels crept into the village of Dutuwewa late
Saturday night and surprised the sleeping residents, said a police
officer contacted by telephone in nearby Horawapatana.
   Military officials in Colombo said the victims included 20
children and five women. At least four people in the village
survived by fleeing into the thick undergrowth, said the officials,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Dutuwewa is about 60 miles northeast of Colombo, the capital. The
village is in predominantly Sinhalese North Central Province but
lies just outside Eastern Province, a main area of operations by
Tamil separatists.
   A Foreign Ministry official in Colombo blamed the killings on the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the most powerful of the Tamil
guerrilla groups that have been waging a bloody independence
campaign since 1983.
   The Tigers issued a statement denying responsibility for the
attack.
   It was the second massacre of Sinhalese civilians in the region
this month. On Feb. 3 at least 11 people were killed in Eastern
Province's Amparai district about 100 miles southeast of Duduwewa.
   More than 8,500 have died in the ethnic violence as the minority
Tamils pressed their attacks on the Sinhalese majority and
Sinhalese-dominated government.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and live
mostly in Northern and Eastern provinces. They claim they are
discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of
the population.
   In the south, parliamentary candidate Somapala Amarakeerthi, his
brother and a supporter were killed Saturday by attackers wearing
camouflage uniforms, military officials said. In the eastern town of
Sammanturai, six supporters of President Ranasinghe Premadasa's
United National Party were shot and killed by unknown attackers, the
officials said.
</TEXT>
