<FIRST>u i BC-Pakistan     02-12 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pakistan,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least Five Killed When Protesters Storm U.S. Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police opened fire Sunday on Moslem
fundamentalists who stormed a U.S. government center in this city.
Doctors said at least five people were killed and at least 30 were
reported injured.
   The gunfire broke out when more than 2,000 fundamentalist
protesters marched toward the United States Information Center to
demand banning of a novel, ``The Satanic Verses'' by Salman Rushdie.
   Police repeatedly opened fire with rifles and semi-automatic
weapons on the charging protesters, who hurled rocks and bricks in
fierce fighting in the heart of the capital.
   Witnesses said the protesters ripped down the U.S. flag and tore
shutters off the building. Protesters who broke into the building,
which had been closed, smashed windows and started several small
fires.
   U.S. officials had no immediate word on damage.
   ``American dogs'' and ``God is great,'' the protesters screamed
as they hurled rocks at the building and drove away scores of police
trying to guard it.
   ``Hang Salman Rushdie,'' one protester yelled.
   Doctors at area hospitals, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said at least five people were killed by police gunfire and many
were injured.
   Pakistan's official news agency said 30 people were injured.
   Police kept the demonstrators at bay for almost an hour before
they gathered strength and moved toward the center, which houses a
library, a cultural center and the offices of the United States
Information Agency.
   An unknown number of police were also injured by rocks, and some
were beaten by the crowd.
   Pakistan, India, and some Arab nations have banned the ``The
Satanic Verses,'' which is named after verses the Prophet Mohammed
removed from the Koran _ the Islamic holy book _ on grounds they
were inspired by the devil.
   Earlier this month, about 3,000 Moslems demonstrated in the
English city of Birmingham to protest the book, which they consider
blasphemous.
