<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     02-12 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Accuses South of Shooting Across Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist North Korea on Sunday accused South Korean
troops of firing across the border at its policemen.
   The North's official Korean Central News Agency said the firing
``gravely threatened the safety of the civilian policemen of our
side on routine duty at the post.'' It did not mention any injuries
or damage.
   ``It was entirely due to the patience and self-control of the
civilian policemen of our side that this incident did not expand
into an arms conflict between the two sides,'' said the agency,
monitored in Tokyo.
   It said several South Korean soldiers fired ``many bullets'' from
automatic rifles Sunday afternoon from the Chosan military police
post in the Demilitarized Zone that divides the two Koreas.
   The post is west of Munsan, a city about 25 miles north of Seoul
and about 10 miles south of the truce village of Panmunjom in the
DMZ.
   ``The U.S. imperialists and the South Korean puppets are
committing one military provocation after another on the ground and
in the sea while staging the adventurous `Team Spirit 89' joint
military maneuvers,'' the report said.
   ``This clearly shows how desperately they are making new war
provocation moves to invade the northern half of Korea, bringing the
situation of the Korean peninsula to the extreme pitch of strain,''
it said.
   Team Spirit is an annual U.S.-South Korean joint military
exercise, described as purely defensive. The North, however, says it
is a rehearsal for invasion and has demanded it be canceled to
improve the atmosphere for North-South talks.
   The two sides have held a number of contacts in recent months
aimed at easing tensions and exploring ways to reunify the peninsula.
   The North and the South have been divided since 1945. They fought
a bloody war in 1950-53 after the North invaded the South.
</TEXT>
