<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--HolyFire     02-12 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Holy Fire,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hindu Holy Fire Burns For 1,128 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hindu family in southern India has been
reverently tending a sacred fire for 1,128 years, a news agency
reported Sunday.
   Tradition holds that the fire, although sometimes reduced to
glowing embers, has never been extinguished since it was lit.
   The Press Trust of India reported that the fire burns in a pit in
the home of Neelakandhan Namboodiri at the village of Cheruvathery,
in the southwest coastal state of Kerala.
   It quoted Namboodiri as saying his family kept the fire burning
by sprinkling it three times a day with coconut, butter and a
combination of nine grains.
   The ritual is designed to attain peace and spiritual and material
happiness, but Namboodiri said it is also costly. The news agency
quoted him as saying it takes about $3 a day to keep the fire
burning.
   Namboodiri said copper plates found during excavations in 1949
say the fire was lit in 861 A.D. by Maharishi Vikala Nethreeyacharya.
</TEXT>
