<DOCNO> AP890212-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-12-89 1143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Crash     02-12 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Crash,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tawanese Pilot Says He Planned Flight to China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a Taiwanese fighter jet that crashed
in China said on state-run television Sunday he had planned the
flight, and Taiwan newspapers claimed he carried military secrets to
the communists.
   A local Chinese television station broadcast an interview with
Lt. Col. Lin Xianshun, 35, who parachuted to safety Saturday morning
180 miles north of Canton, capital of southeastern Guangdong
province.
   Lin said he flew the F-5E jet fighter to China of his own free
will. He also said none of his family knew about his plans. He did
not elaborate.
   None of the Chinese reports made clear whether Lin requested
asylum. In the past, the state media always have given prominent
coverage to military defectors from Taiwan.
   China's nationally televised news said Sunday night that Lin had
been ``warmly welcomed'' by officers from China's air force after
his plane crashed into a rice paddy, reportedly after running out of
oil.
   It showed Lin's mangled jet and of Lin shaking hands with Chinese
air force officers. It said he was treated in a hospital for slight
injuries.
   Earlier reports from China and Taiwan said Lin wanted to find his
relatives in China.
   A China News Service report said he had asked Chinese authorities
to find an uncle, Lin Yuyi.
   ``But authorities have yet to find the uncle,'' said an official
at the state news agency in Canton, contacted by telephone from
Beijing.
   In Taiwan, a relative of the pilot said he believed Lin defected
to China to see his grandmother.
   The relative, who spoke to reporters on condition of anonymity,
said Lin complained that military officers were banned from visiting
China.
   In 1987, the Nationalist government eased a ban to allow all
Taiwanese, except military and government personnel, to visit China.
   In Taiwan, the liberal Independence Evening Post quoted
unidentified sources as saying Lin took ``several important
documents'' about the strength of Taiwan's air force to China. It
said he took the documents from his squadron, which trained selected
pilots as ``enemy forces'' during mock air battles.
   The mass-circulation China Times Express said Lin might reveal to
the Chinese a military blueprint for the defense of eastern Taiwan
from possible Chinese attacks. Defense Ministry officials refused
comment on the reports.
   Taiwan's state broadcasting corporation reported authorities have
taken Lin's wife, daughter and son to Chihhang Air Base for
questioning.
   More than a dozen Taiwanese air force officers have sought asylum
in China and 19 Chinese military personnel have defected to Taiwan
since 1949 when the Nationalists lost a civil war to communist
forces on the mainland.
</TEXT>
