<FILEID>AP-NR-02-12-89 1149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Kemp-Homeless Bjt   02-12 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kemp-Homeless, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outspoken Former Congressman Gets His Chance To Attack Homeless Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Writing 10 years ago, Jack Kemp said the
Department of Housing and Urban Development's programs ``are
consistently misguided and scandalous.''
   Kemp, who took over last week as the new secretary of that
department, is getting his chance to improve those programs, or what
survives of them after a decade of pressure on domestic spending.
   The former New York congressman comes to HUD at a time when the
problems it deals with have gained heightened visibility. The
nation's homeless population is growing and increasingly includes
families unable to afford or obtain housing, according to surveys
conducted by the nation's big-city mayors.
   Kemp and President Bush have both acknowledged the problem of
homelessness.
   Kemp, who offered the harsh description of HUD in his 1979 book
``An American Renaissance,'' last month called homelessness ``a
national tragedy of appalling proportions.'' He pledged new
spending, and last week Bush included increases for emergency
shelters in his new budget proposal.
   But both also have stressed that there are limits to what the
federal government will attempt on homelessness and housing, and
advocates of urban programs are watching Kemp closely for evidence
he will back up his enthusiastic talk about innovation and new ideas.
   ``He's not got a good record, but he has made very positive
statements about homelessness lately, and he has recognized
homelessness is a major scandal that has to be addressed,'' said
Maria Foscarinis, Washington counsel for the National Coalition for
the Homeless.
   ``Now the question is, will he come through?'' she said.
   After a swearing-in ceremony by Bush at HUD's offices Monday, the
new secretary plans to begin visiting inner cities, starting Tuesday
with a trip to Atlanta.
   Mayor Andrew Young will lead him on a tour of housing projects
and to meetings with public-housing tenants, including one at the
Martin Luther King Jr. Center, said Sandra Walker, Young's press
secretary.
   The Atlanta visit is a logical one for Kemp, who frequently
quotes the late civil rights leader the center if named after and
actively sought black support as an unsuccessful rival to Bush for
the GOP presidential nomination. That outreach to blacks is a goal
of the Republican Party under Bush and, as secretary of HUD, Kemp is
in a position to aid that cause.
   Kemp is a conservative Republican who speaks forcefully of
empowering the poor by encouraging the creation of more private jobs
rather than more federal spending. Urban advocates, some openly
saying they want to educate him about the need for more federal
spending, have invited him to visit other cities too.
   ``We're convinced that Mr. Kemp will change'' after seeing
programs firsthand, said Richard Y. Nelson Jr., executive director
of the National Association of Housing and Redevelopment Officials.
   Although there is wide disagreement over just how many people are
homeless in the country, urban advocates are convinced the problem
is growing. The U.S. Conference of Mayors, in a survey of 27 major
cities, concluded last month that the problem increased in nearly
all those cities during 1988 and that in two-thirds of them people
were turned away because shelters were full.
   The mayors also found that one in four homeless people were
children.
   To deal with the emergency cases, Bush proposed $144 million in
new spending in his fiscal 1990 budget, including full funding of
the McKinney Act passed by Congress providing temporary shelter.
   The budget, however, includes no money for additional units of
subsidized permanent housing for low income people, beyond the level
of former President Reagan's proposal. Spending for housing programs
declined some 80 percent during the Reagan years, and a dwindling
supply of affordable housing is what mayors cite as the major cause
for homelessness.
   ``Shelters are not the answer,'' Boston Mayor Raymond L. Flynn
said. ``Permanent affordable housing _ that is the answer.''
   Like Reagan, Bush would rely heavily on use of housing vouchers,
which are certificates for subsidy that renters use as partial
payment of their rents. But critics say those don't help a family
find housing when no affordable units are available, and that HUD
under Reagan virtually stopped subsidizing the construction of new
affordable housing units.
   ``Vouchers work in some housing markets, but when the units
aren't there, vouchers don't get you anywhere,'' Foscarinis said.
   Her organization is backing a bill introduced in the House that
would provide $2 billion to fix up vacant housing units and, backers
say, eventually house 1 million people. So far, she says, the group
is still waiting to hear from Kemp.
</TEXT>
