<FILEID>AP-NR-02-12-89 1217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Sino-Soviet Bjt   02-12 0873</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Sino-Soviet, Bjt,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>``China Card'' Coming Up Aces For U.S. And U.S.S.R. Alike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prospect of the Soviet Union's Mikhail
Gorbachev and China's Deng Xiaoping shaking hands at their upcoming
summit is causing surprisingly little anxiety in Washington.
   Several years ago, reports of high-level chumminess between the
two communist giants would have caused sleepless nights among U.S.
officials, wary of a renewed military and political pact between the
powerful neighbors.
   But Asian and Soviet experts in and out of government say the
relaxation of tensions between China and the Soviet Union, while not
totally to America's advantage, could produce some positive steps in
the Pacific region.
   ``Whatever concerns we might have had four years ago, had this
come suddenly, have now been gradually reduced,'' said Paul
Kreisberg, a specialist in Asian matters with the Carnegie Endowment
for International Affairs.
   ``No one now expects the Soviets and the Chinese to restart the
security alliance they had in the 1950s,'' Kreisberg said, pointing
to comments from Deng that his moves toward easing tensions with the
Soviets are not designed to damage U.S.-Chinese relations.
   Gorbachev is to travel to Beijing in May for the summit with
Deng, marking the first top-level meetings between the two countries
since Nikita Khrushchev met with Mao Zedong in 1959. The sessions
are designed to formally end the 30 years of hostility between the
one-time rivals for leadership of the communist world and ``achieve
a complete normalization of relations,'' Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze announced last week.
   ``There may be some Americans who are anxious about this,'' said
Joyce Kallgren, a director of the Institute for East Asian Studies
at the University of California at Berkeley.
   Ms. Kallgren points to the rapid growth of the economic
relationship between the United States and China, arguing that there
is little reason for the Chinese to disturb that trend. And the
Sino-Soviet relationship ``has a long way to go'' to match it, she
said.
   ``Are we beginning to see the kind of close (Chinese-Soviet)
relationship that we saw 30 years ago? It seems to me that there are
a lot of reasons why that analogy is a very limited value,'' she
said.
   ``There hasn't been much of a wringing of hands,'' agreed a
senior State Department official who follows Soviet affairs. ``We've
had a chance to get used to this idea. ... It's been coming for
years.''
   The official, who spoke on condition he not be identified by
name, said the Soviet move to mend the ties that had been cut in
1960 began under former Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev. The Chinese
felt threatened by the Soviet-backed Vietnamese invasion of Cambodia
and the Soviet intrusion into Afghanistan, and the effort to improve
the atmosphere did not revive until Gorbachev came into power.
   Needing to develop their economies, both nations have strong
domestic reasons to alleviate tensions and reduce military forces
along their 4,500-mile border.
   Washington is not alarmed by the upcoming summit, the U.S.
official continued, because the two countries ``are not going to
create a combined Sino-Soviet threat _ not a military one, not an
economic one, not a political one.''
   The Soviets also are meeting Chinese concerns with their
withdrawal from Afghanistan and support for a Vietnamese withdrawal
from Cambodia. Another positive result could be a lessening of
tension on the Korean peninsula, where the two powers have vied for
influence with North Korea's Kim Il Sung, the experts point out.
   And by appearing to be less of a military threat in the Pacific,
the Soviets are seeking to increase their economic and trade
connections with nations enjoying the Asian ``economic miracle,''
such as Japan, the Carnegie's Kreisberg said.
   Former Secretary of State Cyrus Vance wrote recently that the
United States might see ``more reason for hope than fear'' in the
change.
   ``These two men ... have it in their power not only to end
formally a long period of hostility but also to make an enormous
contribution to peace,'' Vance wrote in a joint essay published by
Time Magazine with Richard Holbrooke, who worked with Vance as an
assistant secretary for east Asian affairs when President Carter
established full diplomatic relations with Beijing.
   Although the United States may lose some of the advantage gained
by having its own full diplomatic ties with two powers that did not
speak formally to one another, they wrote that ``the United States
should not fear the ending of its monopoly of the Big Three summit
dialogue.''
   Other experts note that since the United States has entered a
phase of improved relations with the Soviet Union, it would be
expected that China forge better ties with its own neighbor.
   ``This brings a balance into the (three-way) relationship,'' said
another U.S. official, a specialist in Asian affairs who also asked
not to be quoted by name.
   President Bush's upcoming trip to China _ and his assertion that
he is not deploying ``a China card'' by flaunting relations with
Beijing over Moscow _ demonstrates that the level of diplomacy among
the three nations has reached a new plane.
   ``The need for each nation to play off one off another has
markedly declined,'' the senior U.S. official said.
</TEXT>
