<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan-Defense Bjt   02-12 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Defense, Bjt,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghans Prepare to Defend Link to Outside World</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the last Soviet troops prepare to
leave Afghanistan, a key question remains: Can the Afghan air force
keep open Kabul's airport, the capital's vital link to the outside
world?
   Col. Pavel Vinokunov, commander of a small Soviet guard
detachment at the airport, has no doubts.
   ``The Afghan pilots have been trained in the Soviet Union and
have continued to study here with us,'' said Vinokunov, who has been
in Afghanistan more than two years. ``They'll be able to handle it,
no worse than we did.''
   His words should be put to the test this week, sometime before
Wednesday, the deadine for the Red Army to be out of Afghanistan.
   Kabul, a city of about 2 million, is surrounded by high mountain
passes, which are relatively easy for the U.S.-backed rebels to
block to cut the flow of goods to the capital. Winter snow and
avalanches add to the problem of bringing in supplies.
   With no obvious end in sight to the 10-year-old civil war, the
Kabul airport will be the key link to the rest of the world.
   The rebels are armed with sophisticated, heat-seeking missiles.
   The airport has not come under a rebel rocket attack in more than
a month, and no airliner has been shot down over Kabul. But the
threat has scared off all civilian aircraft except Afghanistan's
Ariana Airline and an occasional U.N. plane.
   On Sunday, though, a U.N. program to bring emergency supplies to
the capital was interrupted when an Ethiopian Airlines jet carrying
the goods was ordered by the Ethiopian government not to fly in.
   Since early January, giant Soviet military transport planes have
been airlifting daily hundreds of tons of flour to help ease food
shortages in the capital.
   Helicopters circle the snow-covered mountains, searching for
guerrillas and providing a screen of flares to deflect their
heat-seeking missiles.
   ``We would like to give it all up right now and go home,'' said
Alexander Kharenko, 26, of Byelorussia. ``But we'll finish the job.
We'll help the Afghans. It's winter and things are rough. There's
hunger in the city. It's no secret.''
   Vinokunov invited Western reporters to the airport to watch their
operation and then to his quarters for tea, sausage, liver pate and
vodka.
   The mujahedeen, as the Moslem rebels are called, say many in the
air force are sympathetic to their cause and will not block the
overthrow of President Najib. Several Afghan pilots have defected to
Pakistan, which supports the rebels.
   Foreign diplomats in Kabul, however, say the air force is an
elite ideologically motivated group that is closely watched by the
ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   Rahman, a 27-year-old pilot who studied for three years in the
Soviet Union, does not hide his feelings about the mujahedeen.
   ``They fire their rockets, but they don't know where they will
land. They have no way of being accurate,'' he said, standing with
several Soviet pilots next to a helicopter gunship.
   ``I like flying and I like to go out and meet them,'' said
Rahman, nicknamed ``Eagle.''
   ``I've seen these groups and wiped them out,'' he said as Soviet
soldiers laughed and patted him on the back. ``I'm good at shooting
them. Come for a ride with me and we'll find some to shoot at.''
   The Soviet departure perhaps will have a psychological impact,
but in practice, the Afghan air force already shepherds Afghan
planes arriving in and leaving Kabul.
   ``Afraid of them? They are afraid of us,'' said Rahman.
</TEXT>
