<FIRST>r p AM-AtlantaMayoral     02-12 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Atlanta Mayoral,0759</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Leaders Square Off In Mayor's Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last time two respected black politicians in
this town ran for the same office, things got downright ugly.
   That was in 1986, when civil rights movement veterans Julian Bond
and John Lewis spiked their 25-year friendship and fought each other
for the congressional seat Lewis eventually won.
   Now, Maynard Jackson, Atlanta's first black mayor, and Michael
Lomax, Fulton County Commission chairman, both want to move into
City Hall as mayor when Andrew Young moves out. Young is prohibited
by law from running for a third consecutive term.
   Lomax, who has had designs on the mayor's office for at least two
years, announced New Year's Day for the Oct. 3 non-partisan
election. Jackson, who has never ruled out another candidacy since
he left office in 1981 because of the no-third-term law, is expected
to announce his candidacy this week.
   Both insist the campaign will be polite and issue-oriented.
History shows they may be wrong, and some sniping and stunting has
already begun.
   ``We're all going to work hard and run a clean campaign,''
Jackson said in a recent interview.
   ``I don't think it'll be dirty,'' Lomax said. ``We all have to
have opponents. I don't view this with hostility.''
   Atlanta political pollster Claibourne Darden disagreed.
   ``Without question, this will be a dirty race. They always end up
that way,'' Darden said. ``They always end up calling each other
racists. You can count on that happening.
   ``This won't be an issue election; this will be a personality
election,'' Darden said.
   Lomax, 41, has served on the Fulton County Commission for 10
years, eight of them as chairman at a time when the northern part of
the county, which encompasses predominantly black central Atlanta,
has undergone an economic and population boom.
   Jackson, 50, laid plans for the expansion of the city's airport
and rail transit system. He also fought to see that a portion of the
construction work on those projects would go to minority contractors.
   In the 1986 congressional battle, Lewis demanded that Bond submit
to a drug test, and Bond accused Lewis of abandoning black voters
for the sake of white corporate interests.
   At one point, Bond said to Lewis, ``I had to wait 25 years to
find out you really don't think I amount to much.'' The men were
barely speaking to each other by the campaign's end.
   In this year's mayoral race, the issues are drugs and crime. The
niceties already are being thrown out the window:
   _ Lomax petitioned members of the Fulton County Commission to
undergo drug tests. He submitted to one himself and passed. Jackson
responded: ``If anyone wants to challenge me to a drug test, I'll
meet them on the steps of City Hall, cup in hand.''
   _ Lomax scheduled vigils at the Bankhead Courts housing project,
where various services were suspended when postal carriers and
telephone repairmen were chased away by the gunfire of drug dealers.
   Jackson showed up, and proposed eliminating the city's housing
authority and turning the projects into tenant-owned cooperatives.
He said cash rewards should be given to residents who turn in their
drug-dealing neighbors _ funds the residents could use toward the
purchase of their homes.
   _ Jackson spoke at a mid-January businessmen's luncheon in
Atlanta's ritzy Buckhead section. Lomax responded by accusing
Jackson of ``sleeping in Buckhead'' while he was ``camping out in
Bankhead.''
   _ When Lomax announced his candidacy during a New Year's Day
rally at another drug-ridden housing project, about 20 protesters,
toting placards reading ``No Lomax for Mayor,'' rained on his
parade. Some in the Lomax camp suspected Jackson forces sent them.
Protest organizer Roy Yancy said they showed up on their own.
   Jackson said Lomax's newfound populist label ``is not going to be
able to stick.''
   ``What we've got is people who view public service in different
ways,'' Jackson said. ``I think one of the things that's going to
come out of this campaign is a difference in the candidates as to
how we look at and treat people.''
   Lomax, who came from Los Angeles, said the voters may not buy
Jackson's image as a concerned native son.
   ``I understand that Atlanta is a city which has a tremendous
tradition of home-grown leadership,'' Lomax said. ``But I think the
issues have gone unaddressed in this city over the last 16 years.''
</TEXT>
