<FILEID>AP-NR-02-12-89 1447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HouseDivided     02-12 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Divided,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Honeymoon's Over In Divided Indiana House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three months after Republicans and Democrats
in the Indiana House found themselves deadlocked at 50 members each
and pledged to cooperate, their marriage of convenience is showing
signs of strain.
   ``The honeymoon appears to be over, and the in-laws have moved
in,'' is how House Republican Speaker Paul S. Mannweiler put it
recently.
   The House became bogged down in a series of disputes after
Democrats began to exert their new power to block a 51-vote majority
and Republicans showed frustration at losing control of the chamber
for the first time in 12 years.
   ``It was strained, and there were times I think people were
frustrated,'' said Rep. Stanley G. Jones, the House Democratic floor
leader.
   Both sides in the House pledged unprecedented bipartisan
cooperation after Democrats picked up two seats in the November
election, which also made Evan Bayh the state's first Democratic
governor in 20 years, and the 100 seats split 50-50.
   After a deadlock on organization day in late November,
negotiations finished on Thanksgiving yielded a unique power-sharing
agreement.
   It called for co-speakers, one from each party presiding on
alternate days; co-chairmen of the House's 28 committees; and new
rules designed to prevent one party from holding the other party's
legislation hostage.
   It seemed to work after the session opened Jan. 4, but events in
the last couple of weeks demonstrated one party can still impose its
will on the other.
   On a day when Democratic Speaker Michael K. Phillips was
presiding, Democrats prevented a committee report on a Republican
bill from moving to the amendment stage on the House floor.
   Two days later, Democrats voted as a block to prevent a majority
and defeat 40 Republican-written amendments to a bill to create a
state lottery.
   ``I think obviously we've been shown that 50 united people can
deny 50 other people the opportunity to have input,'' said
Mannweiler.
   ``It's easy to take 50 votes and stop something. It's not so easy
to get 51 votes and enact something,'' he said.
   During the debate on the committee report, House Republican Floor
Leader Richard M. Dellinger argued that Democrats were stepping back
from a tie-vote rule they had insisted upon during November's
negotiations. That rule allows a bill to emerge from committee on a
tie vote. Previously, a bill had to have a majority vote to advance.
   Dellinger said blocking a committee report ``was like having a
red flag in front of a bull.''
   So, a few days later the lottery bill, which had been expected to
enjoy broad bipartisan support, triggered a partisan debate.
   Republicans offered a series of amendments proposing expenditures
for education and human services programs that Democrats have long
favored. That forced the Democrats to vote against the amendments in
order to preserve the lottery bill as Bayh wanted it.
   After that, Mannweiler said, ``There was some frustration that
partisanship on the part of the Democrats was spoiling what had been
a fairly even-handed system so far.''
   Jones responded that Democrats presided fairly, adding: ``There's
no question there's frustration (among the GOP). There's the same
frustration I felt as a minority member of this body.''
   Jones said he hopes Republicans would ``not get involved in tit
for tat. That serves no one, Republicans or Democrats.''
   Mannweiler said he hopes the displays of power ``will bring
seasoned minds to think there has to be a better way.''
   Other leaders were not so sure.
   ``It appears to me we are headed for a long, strange year or two
years,'' until another election gives one party a majority, said
House Republican Caucus Chairman Dan Stephan.
</TEXT>
