<FIRST>r a AM-ColombianJudge     02-12 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombian Judge,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Judge Kept In Hiding In Detroit, At U.S. Expense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who fled Colombia after being threatened
by the alleged head of a major drug cartel is living in Detroit,
protected around the clock by guards paid by the United States, a
newspaper reported Sunday.
   Consuelo Sanchez-Duran and her husband, Augusto, have lived in
the Detroit area since October under the protection of about 70
guards hired by the U.S. government, the Detroit News quoted
unidentified law enforcement officials as saying.
   It was unclear why federal officials chose the Detroit area as
Sanchez's hiding place, but the News said local police were
concerned that her presence could endanger her neighbors or other
people with whom she comes in contact.
   Sanchez, described by the paper as being in her 30s, fled
Colombia after issuing a murder charge against Pablo Escobar
Gaviria, who the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration says is head
of the Medellin cartel, blamed for smuggling most of the cocaine
that reaches the United States. A rival cartel is based in the
Colombian city of Calli.
   The judge ordered Escobar arrested and charged with murder in the
Dec. 17, 1987, killing of Guillermo Cano, owner of the Bogota daily
newspaper El Espectador. Fifteen others also were charged.
   Escobar, who has been reported to have financed low-income
housing and parks in Medellin, has not been tried.
   Members of the organization are suspected of carrying out dozens
of murders in Latin America and the United States.
   The organization sent Sanchez a threatening letter before she
signed the arrest warrant. The letter, published in Colombian
newspapers in August, said that if she issued the warrant her entire
family, including ``ancestors and offspring,'' would be killed.
   ``We are capable of executing you anywhere on this planet,'' the
letter said. ``There is no place you can hide.''
   Officials say Escobar offered a $1 million murder contract for
Sanchez.
   In four years, drug traffickers in Colombia have killed two dozen
judges, a justice minister, an attorney general, three journalists
and scores of policemen and soldiers. The News said that in the past
seven years more than 50 Colombian judges have been killed.
   Officials told the News the U.S. State Department is paying the
estimated $15,000 weekly security and living cost from $5 million
provided by the 1988 Omnibus Drug Bill and earmarked for the
protection of Colombian jurists who indict drug dealers.
   The DEA helped Sanchez leave Colombia, flew her to Miami and
eventually brought her to Detroit, according to the newspaper.
   Because the News learned and disclosed details about Sanchez, the
government is likely to move her, the newspaper said.
   ``They're going to have to change everything now that the cat's
out of the bag, that's for sure,'' the newspaper quoted one federal
official as saying.
   Escobar also is under federal indictment in Miami on several
charges, but is able to avoid extradition because Colombia no longer
recognizes its 1977 extradition treaty with the United States.
   He was listed as a billionaire by Fortune magazine two years ago.
</TEXT>
