<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAK BROOK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suits and sunglasses worn by Dan Aykroyd
and the late John Belushi in ``The Blues Brothers'' movie were
auctioned to raise money for the handicapped.
   The items were donated by Belushi's widow, Judy Jacklin Belushi,
for the auction held Saturday night to benefit the Ray Graham
Association for the Handicapped, based in the western Chicago suburb
of Elmhurst.
   Belushi's costume _ including shirt, tie, shoes, socks, hat and a
copy of the sunglasses he wore _ was sold for $5,211, said Michelle
Walsh, a spokeswoman for the Ray Graham association. Aykroyd's
outfit, including a pair of his prescription sunglasses, went for
$3,211, she said.
   Auction organizers Sunday were still calculating the total amount
raised, said Mary Wiermanski.
   The suits and glasses were impromptu costumes the actors chose as
their Blues Brothers skits, which graduated from pre-show
entertainment for the television program ``Saturday Night Live'' to
on-air antics, Mrs. Belushi said.
   The original suits were purchased in a New York thrift shop.
   Belushi died in March 1982 of a drug overdose.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kellye Cash, Miss America 1987, will marry
a California high school mathematics teacher July 8, she has
announced.
   Miss Cash, 24, and Todd Sheppard, 25, of Escondido, Calif., will
be married at First Evangelical Church, and plan to in Escondido
following the wedding, the announcement said.
   The two grew up together in California, but never dated as
teen-agers. Their paths crossed again in 1987 when she made an
appearance as Miss America on the West Coast and gave him a picture.
   Sheppard, who also coaches football, basketball and baseball,
flew to Memphis last Oct. 22 and proposed.
   Miss Cash, a spokeswoman for the Drug-Free Tennessee program, is
the great-niece of country singer Johnny Cash, known as ``the man in
black.'' She said her five attendants ``will be wearing the
traditional Cash black.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comic Pinky Lee, recuperating from a major
heart attack, said he plans to change his lifestyle, but not give up
the daily dance routine he once enjoyed in the garage of his home.
   ``I have a little dance floor and a cassette player and I dance
every day,'' said Lee, 72, before he left a hospital here for his
home in Mission Viejo, Calif. ``I hoof it up.''
   Lee, a lisping, baggy-pants vaudeville veteran and early
television comedian, was stricken backstage Jan. 25 at the Peoria
Civic Center during a road-company performance of the Broadway
musical ``Sugar Babies.''
   He denies any regrets over his career, but Lee is unable to mask
the bitterness he feels over lost opportunities, failed comebacks
and his squandered fortune _ he earned a reported $150,000 a year
during his network prime.
   ``I was a rich man. I lost a fortune listening to friends and
making bad investments,'' he said. ``But we've lived a very
comfortable, happy life. Now I'm starting over. And I'm not talking
about show business. I'm talking about life. I have to change my
lifestyle if I'm going to extend my years.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A display of oil paintings by mass murderer John
Wayne Gacy has opened in an alternative bookstore in Boston,
sparking a protest from a member of a victims rights group.
   ``The only way they should display any of those pictures is if
the money being raised is going to the families of the children
whose life he snuffed. Otherwise they should burn (the pictures),''
said Jeanne Quinn, a member of Parents of Murdered Children.
   Gacy was convicted in 1980 of the sex-related killings of 33
young men and boys and was sentenced to die in the Illinois electric
chair. Gacy, who is appealing the death sentence, is being held at
the Menard state prison in southwestern Illinois.
   The Boston exhibit at the Primal Plunge bookstore in the city's
Allston section was arranged by Jessi Rossi, 31, who has been
writing to Gacy for more than a year and is acting as his agent to
sell the paintings.
   ``I'm interested in how he thinks,'' she told the Boston Sunday
Herald. ``In the context of what he's been convicted of, these
paintings are bound to cause quite a thrill.''
   The paintings, which Gacy is selling for between $50 and $130
each, depict clowns, dwarves, witches, Christ and death skulls.
</TEXT>
