<FIRST>r a AM-SatelliteLaunch     02-12 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satellite Launch,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Satellite Launch Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High-altitude winds forced a
postponement Sunday of the launch the Air Force's new Delta 2 space
rocket with an advanced navigation satellite.
   The postponement was announced just 13 minutes before the planned
liftoff after balloon data showed that shear winds several miles
above the launch pad were too high for the rocket to pass through
safely.
   ``We have scrubbed the launch of the Navstar mission because of
the upper level wind conditions,'' Lt. Col. Ron Rand, the Air Force
launch commentator reported. Wind velocities were not reported.
   The launch was rescheduled for 1:30 p.m. Tuesday.
   Rand said a two-day delay was needed to provide rest for the
launch team.
   The maiden launch of the Delta 2 is to carry into space a $65
million Navstar satellite that will enable NATO military users such
as ships, planes, trucks and tanks to locate their positions within
50 feet. The accuracy for civilian users will be 300 feet.
   The Delta 2 is a more powerful model of the Delta 1, which has
logged 170 successes in 182 launches since 1960. It is the first of
three new space boosters the Air Force ordered built to carry
national security payloads after the space shuttle Challenger
explosion in 1986.
   The grounding of the shuttle fleet and the Titan 34D rocket, also
after a 1986 failure, has left the Pentagon with a backlog of about
40 reconnaissance, communications, navigation and other military
satellites to be launched.
   The new Titan 4 rocket is scheduled to debut here next month,
with the Atlas 2 set for a 1990 maiden launch.
   The Navstar satellite, orbiting 11,000 miles up, is to join seven
earlier model Navstars already on patrol. The Air Force goal is a
constellation of 21 of the upgraded payloads in orbit by 1992 to
provide total global coverage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
