<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines-Marcos 1stLd-Writethru a0677 02-12 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Marcos, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Death Would Present Aquino with Challenge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to recast lead and ADD Marcos in critical
condition; picks up 4th graf pvs `Supporters of...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MLA2</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prospect that Ferdinand Marcos may
soon die presents his successor, Corazon Aquino, with the
unpalatable decision of whether to let him return home.
   It also has led to speculation about who will lead Marcos'
followers upon his death.
   The former president has been hospitalized in Honolulu since Jan.
16 and last week suffered a relapse of pneumonia and bronchial
asthma. He remains in critical condition on a respirator in an
intensive care unit.
   Supporters of the 71-year-old Marcos say he is dying and wants to
return to the country he ruled for 20 years until he was ousted in
1986 in a popular uprising.
   Mrs. Aquino has repeatedly banned Marcos from returning, citing
security concerns, but she allowed a Filipino official to travel to
the United States to talk with Marcos representatives.
   The decision suggested she might consider negotiating a deal,
possibly involving the return of some of the estimated $10 billion
Marcos and his associates allegedly embezzled during his
administration.
   Because the government's position is not entirely clear, rumors
abound about an impending deal. There is lively debate among
politicians and commentators on what Mrs. Aquino should do.
   ``National interest demands that we deny him a homecoming,''
wrote the independent Philippine Daily Inquirer. ``In sum ...
Marcos, even in death, should not be allowed to return to the
Philippines.''
   But Senate President Jovito Salonga said Marcos should be allowed
to come home to die if he can settle federal racketeering charges
U.S. authorities filed against him in October.
   Even if Marcos dies abroad, the government would face the
emotional question of whether to allow him to be buried in his
native land.
   The administration has given mixed signals on the issue, and
opinion among politicians and commentators is divided.
   Last week, several Manila newspapers quoted officials as saying
the Cabinet has opted for a ``Napoleonic solution'': banning Marcos'
body from being returned to the Philippines.
   The phrase was coined by Sen. John Osmena, who recommended the
government follow the example of Napoleon. The French emperor died
in exile on St. Helena island in 1821, and his body was not returned
to France until 19 years later.
   Osmena said the government would face mass demonstrations by
Marcos' followers and left-wing extremists if Marcos' body were
brought to the Philippines. Mrs. Aquino says the matter has not been
settled.
   Forbidding a funeral here would infuriate Marcos supporters and
risk portraying Mrs. Aquino as vengeful and unforgiving, especially
since she refused Marcos' requests to return home in May after his
95-year-old mother died.
   ``Considering the fact that we Filipinos revere the dead and even
forgive their misdeeds and wrongdoings while alive, a Marcos burial
in his hometown should make Cory rise above the pettiness and
recriminations of the people around her,'' wrote independent
columnist Emil Jurado in The Manila Standard.
   On Friday, Filipino news organizations received anonymous letters
that said a coup called ``Operation Valentine'' would be staged
around Valentine's Day, Wednesday. Military officers alleged to be
part of the conspiracy included some of Mrs. Aquino's most trusted
lieutenants.
   It appeared the letters were a right-wing attempt to sow distrust
and to pressure Mrs. Aquino into acceding to Marcos' demand to
return home. She dismissed the letters as a prank.
   But military Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa said three
renegade officers, including former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo''
Honasan, met recently in secret to discuss joining forces. Honasan
led an August 1987 coup attempt in which 53 people were killed and
hundreds wounded.
   Another question raised by Marcos' poor health is who would lead
his supporters should he die.
   Several candidates have emerged, including Vice President
Salvador Laurel, who met Marcos in Hawaii this month, and Sen. Juan
Ponce Enrile, whom Mrs. Aquino fired as defense minister in 1986
after a failed coup by his followers.
   Several politicians have pointed to Eduardo Cojuangco, a wealthy
former Marcos ally who lives in California. Cojuangco is also a
cousin of Mrs. Aquino.
   ``The figure to watch is really Danding,'' said Rep. Bonifacio
Gillego, calling Cojuangco by his nickname. ``People admire him
because he did not bring his wealth out of the country and knows how
to take care of his people.''
   Former Labor Minister Blas Ople told The Manila Chronicle that
Cojuangco ``will be a serious competitor within the opposition for
use of assets if he has a mind to use them.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Robert H. Reid, based in Manila, has been the
Philippines bureau chief of The Associated Press since 1986.
</TEXT>
