<FIRST>r a AM-Brites Sub a0700 02-12 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites, Sub, a0700,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf of NEW ORLEANS-dated first item to correct reference
to Reagan as then-president, sted president.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Want your parking ticket fixed? Need a job
reference? Having marital problems? Social Security check too low?
Your son wants out of the Army?
   A lot of Louisiana residents seem to figure their representative
in Congress was elected to deal with any problem for them, no matter
how great or how small.
   Rep. Jim McCrery was called on by a constituent to deliver a plum
to then-President Reagan. He and his staff also found time to
negotiate a telephone bill revision for an elderly couple who said
emphatically that they had not dialed 976-LOVE, a sexy call-in line,
a dozen times.
   Then there was the time Rep. Billy Tauzin got a call from a woman
in Chackbay, La., his hometown.
   ``She said she had a terrible problem,'' he said. ``I guess I was
feeling real good about being a congressman, and I told her `If you
got a problem, I'll solve it.'
   ``So she said, `The garbage man hasn't been coming and the dogs
are getting into my garbage and it's a mess.' I asked her, `Did you
call the sanitation department?'
   ``She waited about three seconds and said, `Billy, I didn't know
I needed to go that high.'''
</TEXT>
