<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;LPoll     02-12 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Poll,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Few Withdrawing Money from S&amp;Ls, Survey Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly all Americans are aware of the crisis in
the nation's savings and loan industry but only a small fraction are
withdrawing their money, according to a poll released Sunday by ABC
News.
   The telephone poll of 509 adults, conducted Feb. 8-9, found that
84 percent were aware of the crisis and that 49 percent had savings
accounts in S&amp;L institutions.
   Of those with S&amp;L accounts, it said, 6 percent were planning to
withdraw their money because of the crisis, and 4 percent had
withdrawn money from an S&amp;L within the last few months.
   Thirty-nine percent of those polled predicted they would be
affected eventually by the problems besetting savings and loan
institutions.
   A majority, 56 percent, said they approved in general of a plan
by President Bush to bail out the S&amp;Ls by selling bonds to
supplement the federal insurance program that guarantees deposits in
the instititions. Thirty-seven percent said they did not like Bush's
plan.
   The survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percent, ABC
said in a release.
