<FIRST>r i AM-Afghan-Airlift     02-12 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan-Airlift,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Airline Backs Out of Emergency Airlift to Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. plan to airlift emergency
supplies to Afghanistan was suspended after a second airline pulled
out of the program, and it may be canceled, officials said Sunday.
   An Ethiopian airliner that made one flight to Kabul last week and
unloaded 32 tons of wheat refused to go again, said Sadruddin Aga
Khan, coordinator of the U.N. Office of Economic and Humanitarian
Assistance to Afghanistan.
   The pilot of the Boeing 707 ``received instructions from (the
Ethiopian government) that he should not proceed to Kabul'' again,
Aga Khan told a news conference in the Pakistani capital.
   The instructions came as the crew prepared for their second
emergency airlift Saturday, he said, adding, ``I'm not able to say
if or when the next flight will be.''
   Early last week, Egypt Air refused to fly into Kabul, claiming
security at the airport was inadequate. Ethiopia Airlines then
agreed to ferry the supplies.
   Aga Khan said he was trying to find out why the Ethiopians pulled
out of the project.
   ``I cannot speculate or extrapolate, (but) some people may be
getting cold feet,'' he said. The United Nations, he said, tried to
keep a ``cool head and warm heart without getting cold feet.''
   The airlift, originally expected to supply Kabul with 360 tons of
food, medicine and blankets over two weeks, may be cancelled, he
said.
   ``Time is running out,'' Aga Khan said.
   The United Nations had hoped to finish the airlift before Feb.
15, when the last of the Soviet Army is to be out of Afghanistan.
   Kabul has been hit by severe food and fuel shortages because of
the bitter winter weather and blockades by Moslem rebels, who have
been fighting the Soviet-backed government the past 10 years.
   Aga Khan said U.N. workers in the Afghan capital identified more
than 30,000 people, mostly women, children and elderly, who were
desperate for help.
   ``I've never seen a man in uniform starve,'' said Aga Khan.
   Moscow has been ferrying food into the capital also.
   Aga Khan also said Sunday he has raised only $888 million of the
$1.1 billion he needs for his ``Operation Salam'' project, which is
designed to help Afganistan's returning war refugees.
   Aga Khan said only 10 percent of what has been raised is in cash,
and the rest is goods.
</TEXT>
