<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-HungerStrike     02-12 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Hunger Strike,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives Weep At Church Service For Jailed Hunger Strikers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ELIZABETH, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of black prisoners
staging a hunger strike prayed and wept Sunday at a church service
held to support the strikers' demands for freedom.
   The service took place at Anglican church in the black township
of New Brighton a day after the government banned all public
gatherings intended to show solidarity with the detainees.
   The service proceeded without interruption and there was no sign
of security forces.
   About 300 detainees are involved in the hunger strike, including
105 at St. Albans prison in Port Elizabeth and about 170 at
Diepkloof Prison outside Johannesburg. Some of the prisoners have
not eaten for 21 days, and lawyers say at least 13 of the Diepkloof
hunger strikers have been hospitalized.
   Many of the detainees at St. Albans have been held without charge
since mid-1986. They include several prominent anti-apartheid
leaders who helped organize an effective black consumer boycott in
1985-86.
   In New Brighton, a township bordering Port Elizabeth, about 400
people packed into St. Stephens Church for the solidarity service.
   One of the organizers read a statement from the detainees which
said: ``We wish to point out to our parents, wives, children and
friends that we will not stop until we are home and free. Any
attempt to stop us will fail.''
   A civil rights lawyer, M.D. Vabaza, said he visited hunger
strikes at St. Albans on Saturday and was told told that two of the
detainees had collapsed in their cells, been taken to a hospital for
treatment and then returned to the prison.
   The service was led by black and white clergymen, and the crowd
included several dozen whites as well as relatives of detainees from
throughout the region.
   The names of all the hunger strikers were read aloud during the
service, which ended with the singing of ``God Bless Africa,'' the
anthem of the anti-apartheid movement.
</TEXT>
