<FIRST>r a AM-NorthTrial-Walsh     02-12 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial-Walsh,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Prosecutor Says Media Could Give The Most Public Scrutiny</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRETT J. BLACKLEDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The special prosecutor for the Iran-Contra
affair credits the press with exposing the case and opening it to
public scrutiny even if security blocks his case against former
White House aide Oliver North fails.
   ``There are two ways of enforcing the law,'' special prosecutor
Lawrence Walsh told a group of Oklahoma broadcasters Saturday night.
``One is the old way of prosecution, which is long, expensive,
cumbersome and sometimes has unforeseeable results.
   ``And the other way is by exposure and education, and that is
what your profession does so well.''
   Walsh, an Oklahoma City lawyer, was in Tulsa to be honored by the
Oklahoma Association of Broadcasters.
   The chief justice of the Supreme Court on Sunday ordered a delay
in the start of North's trial to give the full court a chance to
consider a dispute over the possible disclosure of national secrets.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell had ordered the trial to
begin Monday, but Justice Department attorneys asked the high court
for the delay based on claims that North could release highly
classified documents during his defense.
   Walsh praised the media for its coverage of the Iran-Contra
affair and the events leading up to the North trial, saying he was
surprised how accurate the media reports were about information he
later obtained in his own investigation.
   ``For six months, I got more out of the papers than I did from my
entire staff,'' he said.
   But he said the irony of a strong, effective press is evident in
the administration's request to forbid use of certain classified
documents by North in his defense.
   ``The commitment to a public trial leads to the sometimes very
difficult choices of whether certain information can be used at
trial or whether certain charges must be dropped,'' he said.
   Walsh, 77, said he believes the trial should continue without
further limitations placed on use of evidence, which could lead to
the dismissal of some or all charges against North if he is not
allowed to use the information to defend himself.
   ``It's important to see if we can apply the law to all people,
all levels of government, and to all activities, whether they are
open or secret; and at the same time, preserve our obligation for a
public trial,'' Walsh said.
   Walsh, a former president of the American Bar Association, was
appointed special prosecutor Dec. 19, 1986, by a panel of three
federal judges.
</TEXT>
