<HEAD>Bishop Harris Issues Call of Conscience in First Sermon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Female Bishop, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Episcopal woman bishop preached a Sunday
sermon that mixed evangelical zeal with a call to social activism,
saying that if Episcopal Church leaders had faltered amid
controversy she would not have been consecrated.
   ``We live in a word that oppresses, that dehumanizes, that is
replete with injustices and exploitation, a world God did not
intend,'' said Bishop Barbara C. Harris in a sermon at the Cathedral
Church of Saint Paul.
   ``If Jesus had not taken risks, we would not be saved,'' Harris
said a day after her consecration drew worldwide attention. ``If the
diocese of Massachusetts had decided to play it safe, I would not be
here wearing a brochet and a chimere and a pectoral cross.''
   She received a standing ovation from most of the 400 worshipers,
but one Tampa, Fla., couple left the church with the wife in tears,
saying she was ``heartbroken'' by Harris' consecration. The couple
declined to give their name.
   In a sermon that discussed the temptation of Christ in a modern
context, Harris called on the congregation to resist the temptation
to shut their eyes to issues such as racism and AIDS.
   ``Under the guise of tradition and convention, we temporize with
oppression and compromise with injustice,'' she said. ``We avoid the
problem and the responsibility for becoming involved, and we
rationalize to ourselves, `There's no harm in walking with the devil
as long as he's going your way.'''
   The mood was upbeat in the church.
   ``I felt like I was out of my body,'' said Delois Ward, who came
from Philadelphia to watch her friend of 15 years be consecrated
this weekend. ``It was like the dream I didn't dare dream had come
true.''
   Also at the sermon was Florence Tim-Oi Li, the first woman ever
to be ordained as an Episcopal priest. Li was ordained in 1944 in
war-torn China so she could give communion to those in Macao while
the city was under Japanese siege. But two years later, under
pressure from other Anglican churches, she agreed not to continue
being a practicing priest though she did not renounce her ordination.
   ``I am very, very happy,'' said Li, now 81 and living in Toronto.
``I am yellow. She is black. It breaks down the barriers. ... God
creates boys and girls, two sexes. Now this makes God's will
realized.''
   Ward predicted that the new bishop's warmth would sustain her.
   As Harris entered the church Sunday morning, Ward said, ``I said
to her, `Come here, let me kiss the bishop's ring.' And she said,
`Forget the ring, sweetie, kiss the bishop!'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
