<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-12 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Light Snow In West And Around Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Generally light snow was scattered around the Great Lakes and in
parts of the West on Sunday, with light rain in the southern Plains.
   Oakland, Calif., cooled to a record 40 degrees early Sunday.
Elsewhere around the nation, the coldest spots went down only to 1
degree below zero.
   Wind picked up moisture from Lake Ontario and produced ``lake
effect'' snow across northern New York state. Snow also fell in
Upper Michigan and central New York state.
   Snow showers extended from southern Idaho across northern Nevada,
Utah, eastern Colorado and southeastern Wyoming, and from
northwestern Kansas into south-central Nebraska.
   Rain fell from northern and western Oklahoma across the northern
half of Texas into western Louisiana and in the lower Texas Gulf
Coast.
   The heaviest snowfall during the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST was 2
inches at Grand Junction, Colo., and 1 inch at Salt Lake City;
Syracuse, N.Y.; and Mount Washington, N.H.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 12
degrees at Lander and Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 73 at West
Palm Beach, Fla. Sunday morning's low for the Lower 48 states was 1
degree below zero at Belgrade and Bozeman, Mont.; Burns, Ore.; and
St. Cloud, Minn.
   For Monday, snow showers were forecast in the Rockies, with snow
also falling in Upper Michigan, Wisconsin, northern Illinois and
much of the upper Mississippi Valley. Rain was forecast from the
remainder of the Great Lakes across the Appalachians, the Ohio
Valley and the Tennessee Valley. Rain with occasional thundershowers
was forecast from Missouri across Arkansas, much of Louisiana,
eastern Oklahoma and northeastern Texas.
   Highs in the teens and 20s were predicted from the northwestern
two-thirds of Minnesota across the Dakotas, the upper Missouri
Valley and the northern Rockies, as well as northern New England; in
the 30s and 40s from central New England across North Carolina, in
the northern half of the Appalachians, the Great Lakes, from Ohio
across Illinois and Wisconsin, from the southeastern third of
Minnesota across central Missouri, in the central Plains, the
central and southern Rockies, the Great Basin and the northern
Pacific Coast; in the 70s in Florida and Louisiana; in the low 80s
in the lower Texas Gulf Coast; and generally in the 50s and 60s in
the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
