<FIRST>r i AM-EECMinisters     02-12 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC Ministers,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Foreign Ministers Urge Middle East Peace Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign ministers of France, Greece and
Spain on Sunday said their Middle East tour demonstrates the
European Community's decision to take a more active role in bringing
peace to the region.
   During a press conference at the end of a seven-hour visit to
Cairo, Spanish Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez said
that despite all efforts, he could not predict that 1989 could see
the start of the peace process.
   Fernandez Ordonez, accompanied by Greek Foreign Minister Carolos
Papoulias and their French counterpart, Roland Dumas, met earlier
with President Hosni Mubarak and Foreign Minister Esmat
Abdel-Meguid. They flew in from Jordan Sunday morning and flew on to
Syria after their press conference.
   The three ministers were designated by the European Community's
Council of Ministers to explore peace possibilities in the Middle
East.
   Fernandez Ordonez said the EEC has adopted a new attitude toward
the Middle East peace process, and he said the new policy includes
``the decision to move from a level of declaration to a level of
active involvement. This visit to Egypt takes place within a
framework of contacts with all parties concerned.
   ``We emphasize the necessity of the early convening of an
international peace conference ... we have three objectives: first,
to exchange points of view with the main parties in the conflict.
Second, to contribute to push forward the peace process, and third,
to assess the situation in order to consider further steps to be
taken eventually.''
   Fernandez Ordonez said both the EEC and Egypt believed that the
early convening of an international peace conference was the best
way to bring peace to the region.
   He said his delegation would present a report to the EEC's
Council of Ministers in Madrid on Tuesday.
   The Spanish Foreign Minister said that during earlier
consultations in Israel and with Palestine Liberation Organization
chairman Yasser Arafat, the delegation had felt a positive change in
the attitude of the Israeli people toward peace.
   Fernandez Ordonez said the EEC would do all it could to try to
persuade Israel to join an international peace conference, which the
Jewish state has rejected. It prefers direct negotiations with a
joint Jordanian-Palestinian delegation.
</TEXT>
