<FIRST>r a AM-HospitalEviction     02-12 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Eviction,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital Sues To Dishcharge Elderly Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital has filed suit to evict a
70-year-old patient who refuses to be discharged in a dispute over
whether she needs medical attention after more than 13 months there.
   ``I have serious questions about the way they are handling this
discharge,'' Joseph Olimpi, manager of the Elderly Law Project of
Neighborhood Legal Services, said of West Penn Hospital.
   ``I don't think anybody can order her to go anyplace she doesn't
want to go since she has been judged competent,'' he said.
   Olimpi told the hospital he will represent the patient, Eleanor
Cosentino, in the dispute.
   West Penn's lawsuit, filed Friday in Allegheny County Court,
claims Miss Cosentino no longer needs medical attention, said
hospital attorney Jerry Fedele. The hospital is trying to force her
to be transferred to a county nuring home, to her home or to a
relative's home.
   Fedele said the hospital will ask the court on Monday to set a
date for a hearing in the dispute. The hospital is seeking a court
order to discharge the woman.
   The state Medicaid program paid much of Miss Cosentino's $250,000
hospital bill. West Penn officials say $90,000 in care has been
provided for free since Medicaid discontinued payments in September.
Medicaid acted because West Penn said the woman no longer needed
hospital care.
   The woman and her family claim she needs continuing medical
attention because of recurring infections.
   Miss Cosentino has been a patient at West Penn continuously since
Christmas Day 1987. She was admitted complaining of fever and chills.
   For all but a few days of her stay, Miss Cosentino has been
isolated from other patients because of recurring staph infections
which her doctor, Alejandro Gonzalez, says she got at the hospital.
   Gonzalez says Miss Cosentino is clear of active infection and
would receive adequate care at the nursing home. By refusing to
leave, she is denying scarce hospital space to people who are ill,
he said.
   Miss Cosentino and her family question why she remains in
isolation, where she was as late as Friday night, if West Penn
doctors are correct when they say she is no longer contagious.
   The family also contends doctors treated the infections with an
antibiotic to which Miss Cosentino is allergic.
   The hospital's lawsuit claims Miss Cosentino originally agreed to
be discharged, but changed her mind on the advice of her relatives.
</TEXT>
