<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     02-12 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Estelle Parsons Plays Martha Mitchell</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY86</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martha Mitchell, as played by Estelle Parsons in
``The Unguided Missile,'' is a quirky, opinionated woman far
shrewder than her husband, John Mitchell, at foreseeing the
post-Watergate downfall.
   Miss Parsons does a formidable job. She has the look of Martha
Mitchell, in a floral dress with a superfluous ruffle, the stridency
and the Southern accent.
   Through it all comes a woman of charm, warmth, spirit and brains,
a free spirit believing it's a free country.
   In the play by David Wolpe, which opened Sunday at the
off-Broadway American Place Theater, Mrs. Mitchell does such
uncharming things as get drunk and rant that liberals should be run
out of the country.
   She also discerns post-Watergate events shrewdly while her
husband, the attorney general. Thinking himself vastly smarter than
his wife, he tells her that he'll be loyal to President Nixon and
that the president will protect him.
   Her husband calls her a bigot, says he loves her for it and calls
her an unguided missile because of her unpredictability.
   Jerome Dempsey, playing Mitchell, is convincing when he is
proclaiming love for and frustration with his wife. He's less
convincing when he proclaims how powerful he is, seeming more at
home in a later scene where he admits that he was summoned to the
White House but kept sitting around and never met with the president.
   The play begins the day of the Watergate break-in in 1972, with
Mrs. Mitchell kept a prisoner in her home by a man who says he's
FBI. He gives her pills and drinks, has a doctor give her a shot and
keeps her away from the phone. When Mitchell returns home five days
later, one hand is bandaged and the other arm in a sling.
   Later, she tells reporters she has proof the president ordered
the break-in, while her husband is testifying that he didn't even
tell the president about it. An angry Mitchell tells her that even
her daughter hates her.
   In a final scene, in a hospital bed, Mrs. Mitchell blithely
relies on the reporter she often telephoned at night (Lezlie Dalton)
to do something about her money having run out.
   One is left less with an analysis of political events than with a
multi-faceted portrait of a woman at a time of crisis. Miss Parsons'
portrayal gains a viewer's sympathy and even respect for Martha
Mitchell.
   The play was commissioned in 1984 and has since been rewritten.
It is being performed more than 12 years after Martha Mitchell's
death. Mitchell died last fall.
   Fred Kolo directed. Holger designed the set and lighting, and
Matthew Heineman designed what is seen on TV monitors above the
stage. Nick Searcy, Barry Cullison and Mary Jo Salerno all play
several minor characters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
