<FIRST>r i AM-Bhutto     02-12 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bhutto,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistan's Prime Minister Denies Designs on Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan on
Sunday denied Afghanistan's charge that her army is preparing to
invade that country, saying Pakistan has enough problems of its own
without ``foreign adventures.''
   Ms. Bhutto stopped short of ruling out an eventual confederation
with Afghanistan after Moscow withdraws the last of the Soviet
troops, which have been backing the government of Afghan President
Najib in its war with Moslem guerrillas.
   ``Let's see what the Afghan people decide for themselves,'' Ms.
Bhutto told a news conference on the second day of a visit intended
mainly to emphasize Chinese-Pakistani ties.
   Najib, who uses only one name, alleged Saturday that Pakistan was
massing troops along their common border in preparation for an
invasion. He accused Afghan guerrillas of having agreed to link the
country in a confederation with Pakistan in return for Pakistani
arms and money.
   Ms. Bhutto denied Pakistan was moving troops to the border and
said it would be naive for Pakistan to try to annex Afghanistan.
   ``We've got enough problems of national integration,'' she said.
``We don't need foreign adventures.''
   ``People sometimes propose a confederation with one neighbor or
another,'' she added. ``Stray ideas like this ... may have come up
in the past in relation to Afghanistan. I do not know because they
have not gathered the weight to be considered by anybody.''
   She said Najib made his accusations ``in a bid to divert
attention from the real problems'' he faces.
   In Pakistan, both the foreign and defense ministries called
Najib's allegations ``preposterous.''
   Ms. Bhutto, on her first official trip abroad since her election
in November, met for 3{ hours Sunday morning with Premier Li Peng
and had lunch with former Chinese President Li Xiannian.
   She was scheduled to meet in Shanghai on Monday with senior
leader Deng Xiaoping. The 84-year-old Deng has been in Shanghai for
several weeks, and there are rumors he is undergoing medical
treatment.
   Ms. Bhutto, who arrived in Beijing on Saturday, said the talks
with Li were useful and productive and ``enabled us to establish a
rapport.''
   They covered bilateral ties, international affairs, the two
countries' economies, trade and communications, she said, adding,
``We agreed on everything.''
   Asked about a Pakistani newspaper report that Pakistan has agreed
to buy 75 more fighter jets from China, Ms. Bhutto said only that
she did not discuss planes with the Chinese. Pakistan long has
bought most of its planes and tanks from China.
   Ms. Bhutto said officials of the two countries signed agreements
to encourage and protect mutual investment and extend a trade
protocol to 1990.
   Xinhua said she invited Li to visit Pakistan and he responded
that he'd like to visit this year.
   China and Pakistan have had close ties since 1950, when they
established diplomatic relations.
</TEXT>
