<FIRST>r p AM-JerryBrown     02-12 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jerry Brown,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brown Returns To Politics In Election As State Chair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Jerry Brown, a two-time
Democratic presidential hopeful, says it feels good to be back in
politics after ending six years of self-imposed political exile with
election to a party job.
   ``It feels very good. It feels great. It's been six years, but it
feels like six months,'' Brown told reporters after he won the
chairmanship of the California Democratic Party.
   He defeated investment banker Steve Westly, a longtime volunteer
unknown outside of party circles, by 1,591 votes to 777 in balloting
late Saturday among delegates to the state party's annual convention.
   Brown, who dropped out of public view after ending his eight-year
tenure as governor ended in a losing race for the U.S. Senate to
Republican Pete Wilson in 1982, described the race for the unpaid
party post as his re-entry into politics. He said he hopes to run
for other, unspecified public offices in the future.
   But the 50-year-old two-term governor, who launched his first
presidential campaign at age 36, pledged that he would devote
himself to rebuilding the California Democratic Party and wouldn't
seek any other public office during his four-year term as state
party chairman.
   Saturday's vote was Brown's first election victory in over a
decade. Since winning his second term as governor in 1978, he lost a
series of presidential primaries in 1980 and then was defeated for
the Senate in 1982.
   Asked by reporters if he might run for president or the U.S.
Senate again someday, Brown replied that ``those are the kinds of
intentions that lie deep in one's heart.''
   Westly had argued that Brown would be ``a lightning rod for
political criticism,'' breathing new life into Republican attacks
against controversial events of Brown's tenure as governor, such as
his appointment of unpopular former Chief Justice Rose Bird.
   Other critics said Brown's notoriously chaotic administrative
style didn't suit the detail-oriented duties of a state chairman,
and questioned Brown's new interest in a formal party structure that
he frequently shunned or ridiculed as irrelevant when he was
governor.
   Brown acknowledged all of those criticisms, alternately joking
about his reputation and seriously promising that he has reflected
on both his successes and failure during the six years he has spent
out of the public eye writing, meditating and traveling around the
world.
   ``I can become the media dark hole that absorbs all the negative
feedback and allows our candidate for governor to go on to victory
unscathed,'' Brown said in an acceptance speech.
   Brown said he is seriously devoted to ``the nuts and bolts of
party work,'' laying out an agenda that ranged from redefining
Democratic constituencies to operational goals ranging from the
revival of nearly dormant local Democratic clubs which thrived in
California in the 1950s to new technologies in communications and
fundraising.
</TEXT>
