<FIRST>r i AM-WGermany-Archbishop     02-12 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WGermany-Archbishop,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversial Choice Made For Archbishop Of Cologne</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOGNE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Joachim Meisner on Sunday
officially took over leadership of the powerful Cologne archdiocese
as thousands of protesters rallied against the Vatican's strict
stand on birth control.
   Meisner's appointment and the Pope John Paul II's conservative
policies have caused a widening rift between West Germany's Roman
Catholics and the Vatican in recent months.
   Several thousand people jammed the square outside the massive
Cologne cathedral. One group held up a banner that read ``End the
Papal Dictatorship'' as Meisner arrived by limousine for a Mass
marking the assumption of his duties.
   Other signs welcomed the new archbishop and he was given a
standing ovation when he entered the packed church.
   The hourlong ceremony was broadcast live by the national ARD
television network.
   Cologne church leaders were angered last year when the pope
insisted on the appointment of Meisner, an East German who was
previously bishop of Berlin.
   Many Cologne church leaders felt Meisner was too conservative and
expressed displeasure that their wishes were not considered in
naming a replacement for the late Cardinal Joseph Hoeffner, who died
in October 1987.
   The Cologne archdiocese is one of the most influential in Western
Europe and one of the richest in the world.
   The delay in a new appointment also led to a clash between state
leaders and the Vatican. Under a 1929 agreement, local clerics and
governments are given a say in the selection process.
   In his sermon to the congregation on Sunday, Meisner sought
reconciliation with those who opposed his appointment, but also
clearly reaffirmed a conservative course that goes to the heart of
divisions between West German Catholics and the pope's policies.
   ``My hand is outstretched to all for whom I carry
responsibility,'' Meisner said. ``I ask all to return this gesture
so that we may work together to fulfill the Lord's task.''
   But Meisner also warned against the perils of adopting secular
impulses and straying from church teachings.
   ``The task of the church is not to align itself to the (changing)
spirit of the times,'' Meisner said.
   Referring to the controversy over his appointment, Meisner said:
``Continued public assignment of blame on this or other addresses
will not serve the future path of the Cologne church.''
   The issue of Meisner's appointment has become part of a larger
dispute in West Germany over Vatican policies in recent months.
   In late January, a group of 170 Roman Catholic theologians
released a declaration strongly criticizing John Paul II and the
church ban on artificial birth control.
   The document, called the Cologne Declaration, complained that the
pope recently has linked the church's teachings on birth control too
closely to fundamental articles of faith such as the holiness of God.
</TEXT>
