<FILEID>AP-NR-02-12-89 1828EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0690 02-12 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Goes To Church, Meets With Scholars On US-Soviet Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS first 4 grafs to update with meeting completed; picks up
5th graf pvs, bgng: ``Bush has...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, wrapping up a weekend
visit to his seaside retreat, worshipped Sunday in a country church
where he and his wife, Barbara, were welcomed as ``our old
friends.'' He also met with a group of scholars on U.S.-Soviet
relations.
   Bush invited the academics to his family vacation home to join
him and foreign policy aides for wide-ranging talks, according to
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   Fitzwater called the two-hour session ``open-ended, and not
designed to focus on any particular facet of East-West relations.''
   ``The president is always interested in hearing diverse views on
public policy issues,'' Fitzwater said. ``It was just an
intellectual exercise.'' Neither Bush nor the members of the group
were available to speak to reporters afterward.
   Bush has delayed U.S. participation in the next scheduled round
of arms control talks with the Soviets pending what he has said will
be a thorough review of the current state of U.S.-Soviet relations.
   At the same time, Bush has stressed _ both in his inaugural
address and in his speech last Thursday to a joint session of
Congress _ his desire to work more closely with the Democratic-led
Congress on foreign policy issues.
   Bush reiterated the same theme of closer consultation with
lawmakers and increased bipartisan in a meeting at the White House
last Thursday with leaders of House and Senate foreign relations
committees, according to participants.
   Earlier, the Bushes joined about 60 other worshipers for regular
morning services at Kennebunkport's First Congregational Church.
   Although they are Episcopalian, the Bushes often attend the tiny,
white clapboard church on the outskirts of this southern Maine
seacoast village.
   The Rev. Robert Howes stepped down from his pulpit to personally
address the Bushes, who were seated in a front-row pew.
   ``Mr. president and our first lady, Barbara. You know, I am sure,
how warmly we welcome you, how much it means to us to have you a
member of our congregation.''
   He voiced ``confidence in your wisdom and integrity'' and added:
   ``This is the only time I will address you formally. You are
George and Barbara, our old friends. And we are glad that you are
home with us.''
   The congregation applauded.
   After the service, Bush, wearing an overcoat, stood outside the
snow-coated church in below-freezing but sunny weather and said,
``wasn't that a sweet service?.''
   He shouted a greeting to a group of youths sitting on a fence,
and shook hands with fellow church-goers.
   He also told reporters he was completely over a cold that had
dogged him for two weeks and said he planned to ``take it easy''
most of the rest of the day.
   Fitzwater said that Bush invited the group of scholars, most of
them from the region, on short notice.
   Among those invited were two Harvard professors: Adam B. Ulam,
professor of Russian history and Marshall I. Goldman, associate
director of Harvard's Russian Research Center.
   Also invited were Edward A. Hewett III, senior research fellow at
the liberal-leaning Brookings Institution; Stephen M. Meyer,
associate professor of political science at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology; and Robert L. Pfaltzgraff Jr., director of
foreign policy analysis at the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy.
   With Bush were National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft and
Lawrence S. Eagleburger, deputy secretary of state-designate.
   Bush was to return to Washington on Monday, with a breakfast
speech to a business group in Manchester, N.H., along the way.
   Aides said the Bushes spent much of the weekend unpacking boxes
of personal belongings that had been in the vice presidential
residence in Washington and for which there was no room at the White
House.
   The three-story gray shingle and stone home on a point jutting
out into the Atlantic Ocean is the only home the Bushes own.
   Bush also spent several hours each day working in a small cottage
on the compound that he has designated as an office.
   And he and his wife took time to enjoy a video tape, the movie
``Three Men and a Baby,'' aides said.
</TEXT>
