<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0710 02-12 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0710,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Settlers Protest Palestinians Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with allegation of settlers'
militia; picks up 7th graf `The daily...'; minor editing to tighten thereafter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 Jewish settlers protested stonings and
bombings with a sit-in at a Palestinian mayor's office Sunday, and
five Arabs were injured in clashes with soldiers, Israeli and Arab
reports said.
   The protest underscored increasing settler vigilantism that this
month included angry rampages into Arab towns and stoning of Arab
cars.
   ``Me and my friends decided we should get the message across to
Qalqilya and the mayor that we have lost our patience,'' settler
Shlomo Katan told Israel radio after the group barged into Mayor
Mahmoud Abu Sneineh's office in the West Bank city of Qalqilya.
   The settlers warned Abu Sneineh they would riot if he did not
stop Palestinians from stoning and firebombing their cars which pass
through Qalqilya to and from the West Bank.
   Katan, council head in Alfe Menashe settlement, said the settlers
wanted to talk with Sneineh ``in a good atmosphere.'' But Israel
radio said soldiers spirited the mayor out of the office before
talks could take place.
   A military officer forced the settlers out of the office about
three hours later, the reports said.
   Meanwhile, two left-wing members of Parliament sent a letter to
Attorney General Yosef Harish, claiming the sit-in in Qalqilya was
part of a well-planned strategy by a newly created settlers' militia
of ``a few hundred'' members.
   The letter signed by Yossi Sarid and Dedi Zucker, a fellow member
of the left-wing Citizens Rights Movement, said the mayor of the
West Bank settement of Ariel, Ron Nachman, is one of the militia's
leaders.
   Nachman told The Associated Press no such militia existed.
   The daily Israeli Haaretz reported Sunday that children from
Kedumim and Karnei Shomron settlements, both near Qalqilya, have
begun stoning Arabs from their school buses in response to the
attacks.
   Also in Qalqilya, soldiers Sunday warned six families that their
homes will be demolished after a resident in each house was arrested
on suspicion of helping firebomb Israeli targets, Arab news reports
said.
   Bamahane Israeli army magazine reported plans to pave roads
through Gaza refugee camps to make it easier to chase rioters.
Similar roads built during anti-guerrilla raids in the 1970s stirred
considerable controversy because many Palestinians were forced from
their homes.
   Among five Palestinians wounded in the occupied territories
Sunday was a 22-year-old Gaza man shot in the head, Arab hospital
officials said.
   At least 380 Palestinians and 15 Israelis have been killed in the
uprising, which began Dec. 8, 1987.
   A 70-year-old man from Gaza's Shati refugee camp was in danger of
losing an eye after it was it by a rubber bullet, the Arab hospital
officials said. The army described the man's injury as slight.
   In a West Bank village, about 50 Arab youths marched, chanted
slogans and handed out leaflets urging Palestinians to boycott
Israeli products and not pay taxes.
   Also Sunday, a Palestinian human rights group said a State
Department report released last week fails to go far enough in
criticizing Israel's tactics to quell the uprising.
   Law in the Service of Man, a West Bank affiliate of the
Geneva-based International Commission of Jurists, applauded the
report but said it was ``at times seriously understated.''
   For example, the group claimed 5,500 Palestinians have been
detained at one time, while the American report put the greatest
number detained at any time at 2,600. The report said five
Palestinians have died in detention since Dec. 10, and the group
said 10 have died.
</TEXT>
