<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Election 1stLd-Writethru a0741 02-12 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialist Takes Lead In Special Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf `With 99.23...' with 1 graf to UPDATE with final
results; picks up 12th graf `Fuchigami, 51,...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party, under attack
for a stock scandal and a new sales tax, suffered a setback in a
closely watched special parliamentary election on Sunday.
   In the race for a seat in Parliament's upper house, Socialist
Sadao Fuchigami defeated Kei Oma of Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita's party, according to election officials in southern
Fukuoka prefecture.
   In celebrations televised by the Japan Broadcasting Corp.,
Fuchigami told his supporters: ``The people's complaints against the
(stock) scandal and consumer tax led to my victory.''
   Tsuruo Yamaguchi, secretary-general of the Japan Socialist Party,
said his party will call for the resignation of Takeshita's Cabinet,
dissolution of Parliament's more powerful lower house and a general
election, Kyodo News Service reported.
   Kyodo said the Liberal Democratic Party's secretary-general,
Shintaro Abe, promised his party would accept the election outcome
and go to work on reforms to restore public confidence.
   Sunday's election was the first involving a national office since
the stock scandal surfaced last summer and since Parliament passed a
3 percent sales tax in December.
   The stock scandal has led to the resignations of three members of
Takeshita's Cabinet and more than a dozen other prominent
politicians and businessmen. It also has raised questions about
influence peddling.
   The election was seen as a possible indicator of what might
happen in July when elections are held for half the seats in
Parliament's upper house. Liberal Democrats now hold 143 of the 251
seats.
   Severe setbacks in the elections would endanger Takeshita's
chances of winning another two-year term as party president and
prime minister next October.
   Sunday's special election was for the seat held by a Liberal
Democrat who died in December.
   With all the votes counted by late Sunday night, the election
committee said Fuchigami garnered 751,036 votes against 564,301 for
Oma, 170,778 for Tatsuzen Fujino of the Japan Communist Party and
160,294 for Kozo Maeda of the Salaried Workers' New Party.
   Fuchigami, 51, is vice chairman of the Japan Socialist Party's
Fukuoka prefectural branch.
   An estimated 48.6 percent of the 3.4 million eligible voters cast
ballots Sunday, compared with 74.5 percent in the previous upper
house election in 1986 and 56.8 percent in 1983. The 1986 turnout
was high because the election was held with one in the more powerful
lower house.
   Japan's current Parliament session opened Friday.
   Takeshita told lawmakers that he will ``honestly accept the harsh
criticism'' over the stock scandal and try to restore public
confidence in government.
   The scandal involves Recruit Co., an information services
conglomerate that has been accused of trying to gain favor in
political circles.
   It sold unlisted stocks in a subsidiary, Recruit-Cosmos real
estate company, at bargain prices to more than 150 influential
politicians, bureaucrats and journalists before public trading in
the shares began in October 1986.
   The share prices rose sharply then, and some buyers made nearly
$80,000 in tax-free profits.
</TEXT>
