<FIRST>r a AM-People-MotherTeresa     02-12 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Mother Teresa,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>About 1,500 People Hear Mother Teresa As Former Convent Reopens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLAINFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,500 people crowded into a Roman
Catholic church Sunday to hear Mother Teresa of Calcutta, who helped
reopen a former convent as a new home for part of her missionary
order.
   ``I hope they're going to do something beautiful for God,''
Mother Teresa said at the morning Mass at St. Mary's Roman Catholic
Church. ``It is very important to help each other and share with
each other.''
   The visit by the winner of the 1979 Nobel Peace Prize was later
cut short when she started feeling faint and was helped out of the
church to rest.
   St. Mary's Convent, formerly home of Sisters of Charity but
closed for 17 years because of declining membership, will be home to
13 nuns who are members of Mother Teresa's Missionaries of Charity,
Contemplative Branch, said the Rev. Joseph J. Mirandi, pastor of the
church.
   The nuns will spend seven hours a day in prayer and two hours
visiting nursing homes, hospitals and families in the neighborhood,
Mirandi said. Mother Teresa's Contemplative Branch was established
in the United States in 1976 and there are about five missions in
the country, he said.
   Mother Teresa, 78, founded the Missionaries of Charity, an order
of 3,000 nuns in 87 countries, in 1950. She became known as the
``Saint of Calcutta'' for her work with the poor in that Indian city.
</TEXT>
