<FIRST>r i AM-NIreland-Shooting 1stLd-Writethru   02-12 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NIreland-Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0757,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Prominent Lawyer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with more background on lawyer; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen burst into a home Sunday
and fatally shot a Roman Catholic lawyer who recently represented
the family of a slain IRA guerrilla and a man accused of killing two
soldiers.
   Police said three men broke into the north Belfast house of
Patrick Finucane, 30, and opened fire on him and his wife,
Geraldine, who was believed to be slightly wounded in the leg.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility, but suspicion
fell on Protestant extremists.
   Police were investigating reports that a taxi hijacked in a
loyalist Protestant area of the city was used in the attack.
   The Ulster Volunteer Force, an outlawed Protestant paramilitary
group, has slain two Roman Catholics in Belfast in the past two
weeks.
   Finucane was a prominent Northern Ireland lawyer. Late last year
he was involved in the Craigavon, County Armagh, inquest into the
1983 police killings of three unarmed Irish Republican Army
guerrillas who the families claimed were victims of an alleged
police ``shoot to kill'' campaign against Irish nationalists.
   Finucane, acting for the family of one of the dead, Eugene Toman,
went to the Northern Ireland High Court demanding that three
policemen involved in the shooting be forced to attend and give
evidence to the inquest.
   The coroner had initially directed that the policemen need not
attend but only submit statements.
   Finucane eventually won his case, but on appeal by the
authorities the inquest was adjourned indefinitely.
   In a recent case, Finucane succeeded in having charges dropped
against a man in connection with the killing of two soldiers at an
IRA funeral last year.
   Finucane's brother Dermot, who escaped from Belfast's Maze Prison
where he was serving a term for terrorist offenses, is fighting
extradition from the Irish Republic to Ulster where he is wanted for
questioning in connection with the killing of a policeman. The case
will be heard at Dublin High Court on Tuesday.
   The predominantly Catholic Irish Republican Army is fighting to
push the British out of this Protestant-dominated province, join it
with the Republic of Ireland and set up an all-Ireland socialist
state.
</TEXT>
