<FIRST>r p AM-DukeCandidacy 1stLd-Writethru a0736 02-12 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Duke Candidacy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0736,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Klansman Predicts Victory In Legislative Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `The New...', with two grafs to UPDATE with rally
held. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Duke, who...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Klan leader David Duke has sidestepped
several attempts to derail his candidacy for the Louisiana
Legislature, and is mounting a door-to-door push for the final week
of the campaign.
   Opponents were thwarted last week in two actions designed to
discredit Duke's candidacy. A lawsuit challenging his residency was
not filed, although it still might be later, and militant Jewish
protesters were unable to obtain a last-minute parade permit.
   Duke, 38, and John Treen, 62, are contenders Saturday for a state
House seat from a nearly all-white district in Jefferson Parish, a
New Orleans suburb. Both men are Republicans.
   ``I think we're going to win ... with about 54 percent of the
vote or better,'' Duke said. ``I think that the attacks, the
character assassinations, make people more determined than ever to
make their own choice.''
   The race between the articulate Duke and Treen, a conservative
home builder whose brother Dave was the first Republican governor
since Reconstruction, has generated contributions and comment from
around the country.
   The New York-based Jewish Defense Organization held an indoor
rally Sunday to warn people about Duke. A protest march by the group
through downtown New Orleans was canceled because the group's leader
Mordechai Levy failed to obtain a parade permit 15 days in advance
of the event.
   ``As a man I do not hate Mr. Duke,'' the Rev. Marie Galatas, a
black activist, told the crowd of less than 100. ``But I think he is
a threat and he is very dangerous for what he believes in and what
he stands for.''
   Duke, who was imperal wizard of the Knights of the Ku Klux Klan
before he left the group in 1980, led a field of seven candidates in
last month's primary with 33 percent of the vote. Treen came in
second with 19 percent of the vote.
   Under Louisiana's open primary system, the top two vote-getters
in the primary go into the runoff, whatever their party, if no
candidates gets more than half the vote.
   Attorney Dave Sherman, representing some of the failed
candidates, has delayed until after the election filing a lawsuit
challenging Duke's residency in the House district.
   Sherman said Duke's claims that he lived in a condominium in the
district appear to be fraudulent because utility records indicate
the residence had no electricity until last September.
   Duke, who said he won't talk about his living arrangements
because of threats, will spend the last week of the race going
door-to-door in the 21,000-voter district.
   ``People now know that we can win. People have been waiting for a
long time for a candidate to come across and talk about these
issues,'' Duke said. ``If David Duke wins this race, it will break
the ice.''
   Issues on Duke's platform include requiring welfare recipients to
work, offering incentives for women on welfare to be sterilized,
providing tax credits for education, eliminating affirmative action
programs and keeping a property tax exemption for home owners.
   ``I think nobody really understood how deep the support is for
the programs I represent,'' Duke said.
   Treen accused Duke of jumping on the Republican bandwagon, saying
lower taxes, less government and self-sufficiency have been GOP
goals for years.
   Duke's candidacy has brought widespread opposition.
   President Bush's son, George Jr., appeared in Metairie a week ago
and backed Treen, saying the GOP has no place for Klansmen.
   Roman Catholic Archbishop Philip Hannan and other religious
leaders had a vigil last week in apparent opposition to Duke's
candidacy, although Treen was never mentioned by name.
   ``We cannot allow the philosophy of the white hood ... to gain
acceptability,'' said Rabbi Robert Loewy.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer has said the election of Duke would send a
``terrible signal'' to the country about Louisiana.
   Duke, who joined the Ku Klux Klan as a teen-ager, left after
being accused of trying to sell secret Klan membership rolls. He
began calling himself a white civil rights worker and founded the
National Association for the Advancement of White People, but he
said it is not racist but aims at civil rights for all people.
   During the campaign, he has answered accusations that a telephone
number listed to the Klan rings in his home by saying he is just
trying to make it easier for people to contact him.
</TEXT>
