<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Namibia     02-12 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council To Approve Namibian Peacekeeping Force This Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council this week will approve
a U.N. peacekeeping force in Namibia of 4,650 troops, officials
said, far fewer than the number demanded by black African nations.
   After weeks of lobbying for 7,500 peacekeepers, African countries
and non-aligned nations have agreed to send the smaller contingent
proposed by Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   The five permanent Security Council members _ the United States,
Soviet Union, Britain, France and China _ had pushed for the less
costly smaller force, which is still expected to cost about $416
million for one year.
   The 7,500 peacekeepers would have cost about $700 million, U.N.
officials have said.
   The black African nations contended that cutting the size of the
Namibian force would signal the population there that the United
Nations was more concerned about cost-cutting than ending South
Africa's 74-year rule over the territory, Africa's last colony.
   Black African nations also feared that a reduced peacekeeping
force would tempt South Africa to tamper with elections in Namibia
in November to prevent the main guerrilla group, the South-West
Africa People's Organization, from winning a majority.
   Namibians are to election a constituent assembly that will adopt
a constitution and organize a black majority-ruled government.
   In a report released Friday, Perez de Cuellar assured the black
African nations that the permanent Security Council members would
allow him to dispatch up to 7,500 troops if the military situation
in Namibia warrants.
   Perez de Cuellar also authorized the peacekeepers to carry
weapons, an exception to the normal policy under which peacekeepers
are unarmed.
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said Friday that he expected the
Security Council to approve the secretary-general's recommendations
Monday or Tuesday. The five permanent Security Council members, who
together pay 57 percent of the cost of peacekeeping, contended that
a peace accord signed in December by South Africa, Angola and Cuba
reduced the need for peacekeepers.
   Under the accords, 50,000 Cuban troops are to be withdrawn from
Angola by mid-1991, with half of them out by November, as South
Africa cooperates with the U.N.'s one-year plan for Namibia's
independence beginning April 1.
   Namibia is half the size of Western Europe, but has a population
of 1.3 million, one-tenth of whom are whites. r
</TEXT>
</DOC>
