<FIRST>r i AM-Jamaica-Manley 1stLd-Writethru   02-12 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jamaica-Manley, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0685,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Prime Minister Joins Old Foe In Church</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with Manley, Seago attending church service;
no pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Jamaica-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister-elect Michael Manley and
the defeated Edward Seaga joined about 500 people in church Sunday
for a special ``service of national peace and unity'' after a tense
election campaign.
   The longtime and often bitter rivals smiled and shook hands as
they took seats in the front pew of St. Andrew Parish Church. They
sat next to Governor-General Sir Florizel Glasspole, who is to swear
Manley in on Monday.
   Manley, 64, bruised his right shin Saturday when a car he was
riding in collided head-on with a pickup truck, but he showed no
signs of injury on Sunday.
   The Gothic-style church was filled, and several people stood in
the doorways for the solemn service.
   The congregation, which included U.S. Ambassador Michael Sotirhos
and many other diplomats, sang the Jamaican national anthem and
patriotic hymns such as ``Once To Every Man and Nation'' and ``I
Pledge My Heart Forever.''
   In his sermon, the Rev. C. Evans Bailey, a Methodist minister,
reminded the gathering of New Testament teachings to turn the other
cheek and not take vengeance.
   ``We have left behind us, we pray, a situation in which our
country reached almost the very depths of insanity,'' he said.
   Manley, who was prime minister from 1972 to 1980, was returned to
power Thursday in a landslide victory over Seaga, a conservative who
led the country for eight years.
   Some ballots still were being recounted during the weekend and
final results were not available. Revised unofficial results gave
Manley's People's National Party 45 seats in Parliament to 15 for
Seaga's Jamaica Labor Party.
   Seaga's party had held all 60 parliamentary seats since Manley
boycotted the last election, in 1983, in a dispute over voter
registration lists.
   The prime minister-elect had said he wanted to hold an ecumenical
service before being sworn in Monday to foster a sense of national
unity and patriotism in the aftermath of the hard-fought campaign.
   On entering the church Sunday, Seaga said he expected the new
government to take over in a conciliatory atmosphere. ``I started my
term that way, and I expect this term will start that way, too,'' he
told a reporter.
   Warfare between political gangs left at least 13 people dead and
scores wounded during the three-week campaign.
   The violence was nowhere near as bad as in 1980, when Jamaica
last held a contested election. Then, an estimated 700 people died
during a nine-month campaign.
   Manley and Seaga left the church together, shaking hands with
well-wishers. Manley was briefly mobbed by supporters at his car. At
one stage, he raised a finger to his lips to shush the crowd.
   Glasspole, as representative of Queen Elizabeth II, is to swear
Manley into office Monday afternoon. Jamaica, which gained
independence from Britain in 1962 belongs to the British
Commonwealth, the global association of former British colonies and
territories headed by the queen.
   Seaga, 58, remains prime minister until Manley is sworn in.
</TEXT>
