<FIRST>r i AM-France-Hostages     02-12 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Hostages,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Asks Iran To Provide Proof Of Hostage Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand on Sunday called on
Iran to prove that France had agreed to free a terrorist in exchange
for the release of French hostages in Beirut.
   Iran has claimed that France promised to free Anis Naccache, a
Lebanese national and convicted leader of a pro-Iranian terror
squad, in exchange for three French hostages released in May.
   Naccache is serving a life sentence for leading an assassination
attempt against former Iranian Prime Minister Shapour Bakhtiar in
1980. Bakhtiar survived but a French woman and a police officer were
killed.
   Mitterrand said that when Chirac submitted his resignation
following elections that returned a Socialist government to power
last spring, he did not ask for Naccache's release.
   Speaking on the weekly television news show ``Seven on Seven,''
Mitterrand said that Chirac assured him that the only committment
France had made was to promise ``to restore diplomatic relations''
with Iran.
   ``I have no reason to doubt the words of Mr. Chirac,'' the
president said, adding that it was necessary for ``the Iranians to
provide proof that France has failed to meet its committments.
   ``If such is the case, it is understood that France's word will
be kept. But to my knowledge, this is not the case.''
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas discussed the matter with his
Iranian counterpart Ali Akbar Velayati while on a trip to Iran last
week. Velayati said there was a gentlemen's agreement to free
Naccache, confirmed in telephone calls from Chirac to Iranian
officials.
   The president of Iran's parliament, Hachemi Rafsandjani, on
Saturday repeated the claim that Iran was guaranteed Naccache's
release.
   Interior Minister Pierre Joxe said last week ``unfortunately, we
have no official report, no trace of the conditions in which the
release of the hostages was negotiated by the Chirac government.''
   He said he asked for a written report from his predecessor,
Charles Pasqua, who led the effort to free the hostages, but was
turned down.
   Mitterrand noted in the interview Sunday that Naccache and four
other members of the terrorist gang ``were convicted of crimes.''
   ``They are not hostages. We do not take hostages,'' he said.
   There are 15 foreign hostages in Lebanon. They include nine
Americans, three Britons, one Belgian, one Irishman and one Italian.
The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent
for The Associated Press, who was abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
