<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Fishermen     02-12 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Fishermen,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fishermen Released By North Korea Under Questioning by South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials were questioning
22 fishermen Monday who returned to South Korea after 15 days of
captivity in communist North Korea.
   The fishermen arrived in the port of Inchon aboard two trawlers
Sunday and were met by government security officials who declined to
be identified.
   In the past, fishermen captured and released by the north have
been questioned several days before being allowed to return to their
families. North and South Korea, divided since 1945, are still
technically at war and a peace treaty never has been signed.
   North Korea seized the fishermen and their two ships on Jan. 28,
saying the vessels had illegally entered North Korean territorial
waters in the Yellow Sea.
   On Friday, the president of South Korea's Red Cross, Kim
Sang-hyup, said he had been notified the north would return the
fishermen for humanitarian reasons.
   He said a message from his northern counterpart, Son Sung Pil,
said the decision also was made out of a desire to seek national
reconciliation and reunify the two Koreas.
   South Korea's Office of Fisheries had claimed that the two boats
were captured by a North Korean navy patrol boat while fishing in
international waters.
   The area where the boats were seized is close to the sea
extension of the Korean Military Demarcation Line that separates the
two Koreas roughly along the 38th parallel. North Korea has seized
many South Korean fishing boats in the area in the past, but
returned most of them.
</TEXT>
