<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--PlaneSearch     02-12 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Plane Search,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Walks Away From Emergency Landing, Prompts Search</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYLAND, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot made an emergency landing in a field
when his plane ran out of fuel, then took a bus home without
reporting the incident, triggering an overnight search, police said.
   Officials with the Federal Aviation Adminstration initiated the
search after they received a distress signal from the downed
airplane's emergency locator Saturday night.
   Clark County Sheriff's officials found the Cessna 150 plane
Sunday morning.
   John McIntyre, 42, of Hazelwood, was en route to Jacksonville,
Ill., from Creve Coeur, Ill., when he ran out of fuel, said a
sheriff's spokesman. He landed about 11:30 a.m. Saturday in a wooded
pasture in the northeast corner of Missouri.
   He was not injured and the plane received only minor damage.
McIntyre hitched a ride to nearby Keokuk, Iowa, where he caught a
bus home, officials said.
   Clark County officials, the Missouri State Highway Patrol, the
FAA and the National Transportation Safety Board were investigating
why McIntyre did not report the incident and why he strayed from his
course.
</TEXT>
