<FILEID>AP-NR-02-12-89 2152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mideast-Soviet     02-12 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mideast-Soviet,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister to Visit Jordan, Egypt This Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
will visit Jordan and Egypt this month, officials said, indicating
an increasing Soviet role in the Middle East conflict.
   King Hussein said the Soviet minister will visit Jordan on Feb.
19 and the king indicated he had little objection to renewed Soviet
relations with Israel if they lead to an Arab-Israeli peace
conference.
   ``If there is a move toward the establishment of peace, obviously
any objections to anyone restoring relations with anyone in this
part of the world become of secondary importance,'' Hussein said in
an interview with Japanese reporters.
   Restoration of Soviet-Israeli relations, severed during the 1967
Arab-Israeli war, are an Israeli condition for the Soviet role in
Middle East peace talks demanded by Hussein and other Arab leaders.
   Hussein said he was ``quite optimistic'' that an international
conference peace could take place soon, given recent U.S. and Soviet
efforts to solve other regional problems.
   He urged Israeli leaders to abandon their opposition to involving
the Palestine Liberation Organization in peace talks.
   ``I can't see any solution to the Palestinian problem without the
participation of the Palestinians,'' the king said.
   Hussein refused to commit Jordan to a confederation with a
proposed Palestinian state _ an idea floated earlier partly to
overcome Israeli and American opposition to an independent
Palestinian entity.
   In Cairo, Soviet Ambassador Gennady Zhuravlev told reporters
Shevaradnadze is expected to visit the Egyptian capital some time
this month, though no exact date has been set. Zhuravlev spoke to
reporters after a meeting with Egypt's Foreign Minister Esmat
Abdel-Meguid.
   The last Soviet foreign minister to visit Cairo was Andrei
Gromyko in 1975, three years after late President Anwar Sadat
expelled 15,000 Soviet military advisers in anger over Moscow's
refusal to supply Egypt the arms it wanted.
   Relations between Cairo and Moscow remained sour during the 1970s
and improved only after President Hosni Mubarak took office in 1981.
Diplomatic ties were resumed at the ambassadorial level in 1984.
</TEXT>
