<HEAD>Suspicious Blaze Whips Through Historic Shoe District</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAVERHILL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators suspect a fire that whipped
through a historic shoe manufacturing district and destroyed six
buildings was set by arsonists, police said.
   No one was seriously injured in the blaze, which caused an
estimated $1 million damage as it roared out of control for more
than two hours Saturday night, officials said.
   ``Nothing's for certain yet, but they do have reason to believe
at this point that it was of suspicious origin,'' said police Sgt.
Richard T. Smith. ``One thing was the speed with which it took off.''
   The fire apparently broke out at about 10:30 p.m. in the former
Birney Shoe Co. building, which was erected in 1882.
   Several of the buildings housed shops, a tanning salon, pizza
parlor, offices and other small businesses in the district, which
was once the city's shoe manufacturing center.
