<FIRST>u i AM-Iran 1stLd-Writethru a0706 02-12 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini's Heir Calls for End to Extremism, Questions Who Won War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-10 `Montazeri also...each other'' with 4 grafs
to UPDATE with opposition party calling for democratic reforms; picksup
11th graf pvs: `Speaking about...' Minor editing throughout to trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The designated successor to Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini called for an end to extremism in remarks
published Sunday and urged Iran's leaders to ``make up for past
mistakes'' that isolated the Islamic republic.
   Ayatollah Hussein-Ali Montazeri's comments, published by the
official Islamic Republic News Agency and Tehran's Abrar daily,
echoed recent calls by other Iranian leaders for critical
self-examination as the Iranian revolution moves into its second
decade.
   Montazeri went further, however, by questioning the official
doctrine that Iran won the eight-year war against Iraq.
   ``People in the world got the idea that our business in Iran is
just murdering people,'' Montazeri was quoted as saying in criticism
of the self-imposed isolation. He spoke in the holy city of Qom on
Saturday at the climax of 10 days of celebrations marking the
revolution's 10th anniversary.
   Montazeri, 64, has been increasingly critical of the revolution's
shortcomings and repeatedly has called for a relaxation of its
stringent religious, social and political restrictions.
   In another indication of a more open political atmosphere, the
Iranian news agency reported Sunday that Iran's only legalized
opposition party demanded that the government allow opposition
newspapers and provide security needed for open political activity.
   It quoted Ibrahim Yazdi, an official of the Iran Freedom Movement
Party, as saying the opposition group is not opposed to the rule of
the Islamic clergy. ``Provided a free press, freedom of gatherings
and freedom of thought, we will not turn our backs,'' he was quoted
as saying.
   The group said it would participate in any open presidential
elections.
   Montazeri's latest criticism was his strongest, and all the more
telling because it was delivered on the anniversary of the day in
1979 when the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi's government collapsed
and Khomeini's revolutionaries took over.
   Speaking about the Iran-Iraq, Montazeri asked a question that a
year ago would have been considered political heresy: ``Did we
succeed in doing well during the imposed war, or did the enemies who
imposed it turn out to be the victors?''
   Hostilities halted Aug. 20 after Iran, battered by a string of
military defeats, accepted a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire a year after
Iraq said it was willing to do so.
   ``We should consider how many people we lost, how many splendid
young men were martyred, how many cities were destroyed. We should
take all these into account, then if we say we have made a mistake,
we should repent,'' Montazeri said.
   ``We used slogans that frightened the world ... Have we succeeded
in protecting the revolution and realizing its objectives? Have we
delivered the promises we gave to the people?''
   His hard-hitting comments follow unusually frank interviews by
other Iranian leaders, including Parliament Speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani and Chief Justice Musavi Ardebili, in which they
acknowledged that Iran's war strategy was flawed and that U.S.
intervention tipped the scales against Tehran.
   Montazeri's remarks contrasted with a Saturday speech by
President Ali Khamenei to a rally in Tehran, which was long on
praise for the revolution's survival and short on criticism of its
failings.
   Khamenei admitted there were differences in Iran's leadership but
denied a power struggle exists.
   Montazeri touched on one of the points of disagreement by
advocating that Iranians who fled abroad be allowed to return to
help rebuild an economy nearly ruined by the war.
   ``Those abroad are terrified,'' he said, in an apparent reference
to a wave of executions in Iran over the past six months.
   Iranian leaders have admitted some political prisoners have been
executed. Dissident Iranians claim as many as 12,000 people have
been killed. The United Nations and Amnesty International estimate
there have been 1,000 executions.
   ``Set aside past mistakes and harsh treatment. Extremism is to
our detriment. Try to treat (the exiles) with affection and Islamic
behavior,'' Montazeri said.
   Montazeri praised Khomeini's decision last week to pardon all
political prisoners except ``those with sinister intentions,'' a
reference to about 900 considered hard-core opponents.
   ``Filling the prisons will not heal any wounds,'' Montazeri
declared.
</TEXT>
