<HEAD>Weekend Gang Violence Kills Pregnant Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival gangs armed with assault rifles were
involved in several weekend shootings that killed two people,
including a pregnant teen-ager early Sunday, police said.
   Andrea Garrett, 19, of Los Angeles, was shot several times in the
upper torso as she was standing with a group of people outside a
housing project just after midnight, said Detective John Spreitzer.
   Ms. Garrett, who was eight months pregnant, was pronounced dead
at the scene, east of downtown. A 19-year-old man was shot several
times in the back with the same assault rifle that struck Ms.
Garrett and was seriously wounded, Spreitzer said.
   A 26-year-old Los Angeles man also was wounded after being hit
several times with shotgun pellets, Spreitzer said.
   The attack was believed to be part of a narcotics turf war in the
project, said Lt. Sergio Robleto. The assailants, who shouted gang
slogans as they fled the scene, only were described as three males,
the detective said.
   In a drive-by attack on Saturday, Ruben Castro, 22, was struck by
gunfire from a passing car at 5:30 a.m. while sitting in a car with
another person at an intersection in suburban El Monte, said
sheriff's Deputy Dan Cox.
   Castro drove himself to a friend's house where paramedics treated
him before taking him to Greater El Monte Community Hospital, where
he died.
   Earlier Saturday, shots fired from a passing car into a group of
people wounded a 17-year-old boy in the legs, Sgt. Carl Heintz said.
The boy was hospitalized in stable condition.
   A man was wounded in a similar attack Friday night when shots
were fired into a gathering of people in south-central Los Angeles,
Lt. Mike Chambers said. The 18-year-old man was in stable condition.
