<HEAD>Guerrillas Bomb Government Palace and University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas on Sunday claimed
responsibility for launching an attack outside the presidential
palace and setting off a bomb at a university.
   There were no reports of injuries and the palace was not damaged,
but the campus explosion shattered windows and destroyed furniture.
   The pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, which claimed
responsibilty in phone calls to local newspapers, left flyers near
the campus explosion demanding guarantees that their military
leader, Victor Polay, not be harmed.
   Polay was captured Feb. 3 in Huancayo, an Andean city 140 miles
east of Lima.
   The newspaper Expreso said in its Sunday edition that attackers
fired four grenades at the Government Palace on Saturday night. It
said three of the four grenades exploded in the air and the fourth
hit the roof of the building that houses the offices and residence
of President Alan Garcia.
   Police denied grenades were fired. They said a strong blast was
heard in a nearby zone of the palace called Polvos Azules. Security
forces exchanged gunfire with three men who fled in the night.
   Shortly after the explosion, policemen and soldiers surrounded
the palace, blocking the streets to vehicles and pedestrians.
   An hour after the incident, dynamite exploded in a building of
the Garcilazo de la Vega University, a block away from the U.S.
ambassador's residence in one of the main avenues of the city.
   The Government Palace have been attacked five times in the last
seven years, but no injuries or severe damage have resulted.
   The Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement has been active in Peru
since 1984. In November 1987, Polay led a guerrilla group in a
jungle region northeast of Lima.
