<FILEID>AP-NR-02-12-89 1856EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-LILCO     02-12 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LILCO,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parties Disputing Nuclear Plant To Meet On Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parties involved in the dispute over the Long
Island Lighting Co. and its idle Shoreham nuclear power plant spent
Sunday pondering a federal judge's ruling and a proposed settlement
that may finally end the debate.
   ``There are lots of things to think about,'' said Judith Vladeck,
an attorney representing Lilco ratepayers, who was in her Manhattan
office Sunday going over the weekend's developments with her clients.
   On Saturday, U.S. District Judge Jack B. Weinstein threw out a
$22.8 million judgment against Lilco, saying the case involving
electricity rates belonged before the state Public Service
Commission, not the courts.
   On Monday, the parties were scheduled to gather in Weinstein's
chambers to review a settlement outlined Saturday by a federal
mediator that would close the $5.4 billion Shoreham plant on Long
Island, which has never operated commercially.
   Suffolk County officials also planned to meet Monday to consider
appealing Weinstein's ruling.
   ``I'm quite confident that it is in the interest of all the
parties to settle this case (Monday),'' the mediator, Kenneth R.
Feinberg, said Sunday.
   Feinberg said the settlement calls for the shutdown of Shoreham
and a $400 million reduction in Lilco's planned rate increases over
the next 10 years.
   The settlement would take effect if Gov. Mario Cuomo approves it
within 15 days of its approval by Lilco and Suffolk County.
   The financially troubled utility company and Cuomo declined
comment on the proposed settlement; a spokesman for Suffolk County
Executive Patrick Halpin expressed cautious acceptance.
   Under a similar settlement proposed by the governor last year,
the state would have bought Shoreham for $1 and closed it; Lilco was
to get annual rate increases of about 5 percent. The proposal was
criticized as too expensive to ratepayers and it died when the
Legislature failed to act on it.
   Feinberg's proposal reduces the proposed increases by about $400
million and contains provisions to settle a lawsuit by Lilco against
the town of Brookhaven, which the utility says overassessed Shoreham
by more than $500 million.
   Weinstein's ruling came more than two months after a federal jury
found that Lilco had lied to obtain rate increases to help pay for
Shoreham. The verdict exposed Lilco to the possibility of a
class-action suit that could have resulted in billions of dollars in
damages.
   Though he allowed the trial to continue, Weinstein ruled Saturday
that the issue should not be decided in federal court under the
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act.
   ``What the trial proved ... was that RICO cannot, and should not,
be applied in a case such as this to permit a federal jury in a
civil case to second guess the ratemaking authority of the state,''
Weinstein ruled.
   Construction on the Shoreham plant, 60 miles east of Manhattan,
began in 1973 and it was largely finished a decade later.
   But legal objections to the plant were raised by state and local
governments and many Long Island residents, who contend they could
not safely evacuate the area should there be a plant emergency. The
delays pushed the cost of Shoreham to $5.4 billion, more than 70
times the original estimate.
   The dispute has taken LILCO to the brink of bankruptcy several
times.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
