<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-Markets     02-12 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Opens Higher, Stock Prices Fall In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar started the trading week substantially
higher against the Japanese yen on Monday, while stock prices
declined.
   The dollar opened at 128.60 yen, up 0.95 yen from Friday's close
of 127.65 yen.
   A rise in prime lending rates by many American commercial banks
and the news of a higher-than-expected U.S. producer price index for
January, both announced on Friday, combined to spur the dollar's
rally, said a dealer from the Bank of Tokyo.
   The dealer, who spoke anonymously, said the report showing the
nation's producer price index for finished goods rose 1 percent last
month was ``stunning news.''
   Also Friday, numerous banks in the United States raised their
prime lending rates from 10.5 percent to 11 percent.
   The rate is closely watched because bankers use it as a basis for
calculating interest on corporate loans and for determining various
types of fixed and adjustable-rate consumer loans, including home
equity loans.
   Higher U.S. interest rates tend to make the dollar more
attractive to foreign investors.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which closed at a record 32,131.99 points on
Friday, lost 179.91 points, or 0.55 percent, shortly after the
market opened to move to 31,952.08.
</TEXT>
